{"title_page": "Asafo Aumua", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n|           name = Asafo Aumua\n|          image =\n|     image_size =\n|        caption =\n|       fullname = Asafo Junior Aumua\n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|05|05|df=y}}\n|    birth_place = [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], New Zealand\n|         height = {{convert|177|cm|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n|         weight = {{convert|108|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}\n|         school = [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St. Patrick's College Silverstream]]\n|     university =\n|      relatives =\n|     occupation =\n|         spouse =\n|       position = [[Hooker (rugby union)|Hooker]]\n|    currentclub = [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]], [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n|     allblackno = 1163\n|     allblackid = 1163\n|    youthyears1 =\n|    youthclubs1 =\n|         years1 = 2016\u2013\n|         clubs1 = [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]]\n|          apps1 = 42\n|        points1 = 95\n|         years2 = 2018\u2013\n|         clubs2 = [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n|          apps2 = 21\n|        points2 = 5\n|      repyears1 = 2016\u20132017\n|       repteam1 = [[New Zealand national under-20 rugby union team|New Zealand U20]]\n|       repcaps1 = 14\n|     reppoints1 = 35\n|      repyears2 = 2017\n|       repteam2 = [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]]\n|       repcaps2 = 2\n|     reppoints2 = 0\n|     clubupdate = 13 March 2020\n|      repupdate = 13 March 2020\n}}\n\n'''Asafo Junior Aumua''' ({{IPAc-en|a\u028a|\u02c8|m|u\u02d0|\u0259}}; born 5 May 1997) is a New Zealand professional [[rugby union]] footballer who plays as a [[Hooker (rugby union)|hooker]] for New Zealand franchise [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]] and the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand national team]]. In his youth career, he was selected to play in the 2016 and 2017 [[World Rugby Under 20 Championship|World Rugby Under 20 Championships]] for [[New Zealand national under-20 rugby union team|New Zealand]] and took part in [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St. Patrick's College Silverstream]] first XV, the top representative team in secondary school.\n\nAumua represents the [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]] provincial team and made his [[Professional sport|professional]] debut for the union in 2016 at the age of 19. He spent two seasons at the [[Mitre 10 Cup]] side, before earning a place in the Hurricanes [[2018 Super Rugby season|2018 Super Rugby]] squad.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hurricanes.co.nz/news/article/hurricanes-2018-squad-announced/ | title=HURRICANES 2018 SQUAD ANNOUNCED | work=Hurricanes | date=1 November 2017 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> He won a championship with Wellington in 2017 and was named [[New Zealand Rugby Union|NZRU]] Age Grade Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/all-blacks/99875399/Sam-Whitelock-claims-player-of-the-year-as-Black-Ferns-grab-team-of-year-at-NZ-Rugby-Awards | title=Sam Whitelock claims player of the year as Black Ferns grab team of year at NZ Rugby Awards | work=Stuff | date=15 December 2017 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> He has scored 27 career [[Try (rugby)|tries]] in all competitions. Aumua made his senior international debut for New Zealand in November 2017 at the age of 20, becoming one of the [[List of New Zealand national rugby union team player records#Youngest players|youngest players]] to represent New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://stats.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/records/player/youngest_appearance.html?id=8;type=team | title=Youngest appearance | work=ESPN Scrum | date=3 August 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> He played in the [[2017 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2017 northern end-of-year tour]].\n\n== Early life ==\nAsafo Junior Aumua was born on 5 May 1997 in [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], the son of Tautua and Lisa Aumua.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/abs-squad/98146032/emotional-day-for-aumua-family-as-asafo-earns-his-first-on-his-all-blacks-callup | title=Emotional day for Aumua family as Asafo earns his first on his All Blacks callup | author=Liam Hyslop | work=Stuff | date=23 October 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> Growing up in [[Naenae]], he attended [[Naenae Intermediate School]] and [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St. Patrick's College Silverstream]].<ref name=\"new-all-black-asafo-aumua\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/all-blacks/98207504/big-things-have-been-predicted-for-new-all-black-asafo-aumua-from-a-young-age | title=Young All Blacks hooker Asafo Aumua tipped for stardom after meteoric rise | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=26 October 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> While at secondary school, Aumua was chosen to play for Silverstream first XV at the age of fifteen.<ref name=new-all-black-asafo-aumua/> He spent three years representing the side, winning two regional sevens titles and was a part of two unbeaten runs through the round robin of the [[Wellington Institute of Technology|WelTec]] premiership.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=2555 | title=Asafo Aumua - Hard work is more important than hype | author=Adam Julian | work=Club Rugby | date=15 August 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> In [[rugby sevens]], Aumua was named player of the tournament at the Marist College event, and joined the New Zealand Marist sevens squad for their tour of [[Samoa]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=1236 | title=St Pat?s Silverstream defend Marist College Sevens title | author=Adam Julian and Steven White | work=Club Rugby | date=8 February 2015 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> He primarily played hooker, but also played [[Centre (rugby union)|second five-eighth]], [[Prop (rugby union)|prop]], and [[Number 8 (rugby union)|number 8]] at first XV level.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=1808 | title=School leavers to watch in 2016 Wellington Premier rugby | author=Adam Julian and Steven White | work=Club Rugby | date=22 March 2016 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter his last year at Silverstream, Aumua was enrolled into the 26-man [[New Zealand Schoolboys|New Zealand Secondary Schools]] team for a three-match international series in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11513291 | title=Rugby: NZ Secondary Schools squad named | work=New Zealand Herald | date=15 September 2015 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> He was involved in a 24-point victory over [[Australian Schoolboys rugby union team|Australian Schoolboys]], where he scored a try that was recognized by [[Green and Gold Rugby]] journalist Nic Darveniza as try of the match, extending New Zealand's lead in the second half.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.greenandgoldrugby.com/nz-schools-give-aussies-a-masterclass/ | title=NZ Schools give Aussies a masterclass | author=Nic Darveniza | work=Green & Gold Rugby | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> Aumua was one of six Wellington players to represent [[New Zealand national under-20 rugby union team|New Zealand]] at the World Rugby Under 20 Championships in [[Manchester]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allblacks.com/News/29146/nz-squad-named-for-world-rugby-under-20-championship | title=NZ squad named for World Rugby Under 20 Championship | work=All Blacks | date=10 May 2016 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> The following year, he was named to travel to [[Tbilisi]], in his second Under 20 World Championship campaign.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://rugbyheartland.co.nz/wp/2017/05/09/nz-under-20-squad-named-for-rugby-world-championship-in-georgia/ | title=NZ UNDER 20 SQUAD NAMED FOR RUGBY WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP IN GEORGIA | author=admin_hland | work=Rugby Heartland | date=9 May 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> New Zealand won their sixth title after defeating [[England national under-20 rugby union team|England]] 64\u201317 in a record score in a final, scoring ten tries to three.<ref name=\"win-world-rugby-championship\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11878903 | title=Rugby: New Zealand under-20s win World Rugby Championship in style | author=Campbell Burnes | work=New Zealand Herald | date=19 June 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> Aumua scored a [[Hat-trick#Rugby_football|hat-trick]], including one solo try in which he beat no less than six defenders.<ref name=win-world-rugby-championship/> He became only the second player to score a hat-trick in a final.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.worldrugby.org/u20/video/259852 | title=Asafo Aumua scores incredible hat-trick in World Rugby U20 Championship final | work=World Rugby | date=19 June 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\n=== 2016\u201318 ===\nDuring the [[2016 Mitre 10 Cup|2016 season]], at 19 years old, he made his first professional team debut when he came on as a reserve forward during the opening match against [[Hawke's Bay Rugby Union|Hawke's Bay]] at [[McLean Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/provincial/83321318/greg-foe-to-captain-wellington-against-hawkes-bay-as-brad-shields-recovers-from-injury | title=Greg Foe to captain Wellington against Hawke's Bay as Brad Shields recovers from injury | author=Liam Hyslop | work=Stuff | date=19 August 2016 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref> Representing the Wellington under-19 team in [[Taupo]], Aumua was ordered back after [[Leni Apisai]] failed concussion protocols in preparation against [[Northland Rugby Union|Northland]].<ref name=\"asafo-Aumua-came-as-no-surprise\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/rugby-world-cup/84594057/The-performance-of-Wellington-hooker-Asafo-Aumua-came-as-no-surprise-to-some | title=The performance of Wellington hooker Asafo Aumua came as no surprise to some | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=23 September 2016 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref> He scored three tries in the fixture, making him just the fourth hooker to register a hat-trick in the competition's history.<ref name=asafo-Aumua-came-as-no-surprise/> Aumua was the side's leading try-scorer with six in 10 games.<ref name=\"aumua-strong-contender\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/all-blacks/96436634/Wellington-sensation-Asafo-Aumua-strong-contender-for-All-Blacks-apprentice-role | title=Wellington sensation Asafo Aumua strong contender for All Blacks apprentice role | author=Marc Hinton | work=Stuff | date=2 September 2017 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHis performance at national age grade level in 2017 impressed Wellington head coach Chris Gibbes ahead of the [[2017 Mitre 10 Cup]], and he was subsequently renamed in the squad for their upcoming season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=2550 | title=New caps in Wellington Lions squad for 2017 | work=Club Rugby | date=11 August 2017 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref> Aumua started well for Wellington, scoring three tries through the first three games of the competition.<ref name=aumua-strong-contender/> His scoring ability was noted after beating [[Outside backs (rugby union)|outside back]] defender [[George Bridge]] for a {{convert|60|m|yd|abbr=off}} solo try.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rugbydump.com/2017/09/5895/wellington-hooker-asafo-aumua-steps-fullback-to-score-incredible-60m-try | title=Wellington Hooker Asafo Aumua steps fullback to score incredible 60m try | work=Rugby Dump | date=18 September 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref> It saw Aumua place fourth-equal in the overall leading try-scorers with fellow [[Rugby union positions|front rower]] and teammate, [[Alex Fidow]] on seven tries each.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mitre10cup.co.nz/News/31619/statchat-the-leading-players-in-the-mitre-10-cup | title=STATCHAT: The leading players in the Mitre 10 Cup | work=Mitre 10 Cup | date=16 October 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing his 2017 provincial campaign, Aumua was called up into the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] for the [[2017 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2017 end of year tour]] despite the fact that he had not even made his [[Super Rugby]] debut.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11941981 | title=Rugby: Asafo Aumua has joined an elite but largely unhappy All Blacks club | work=New Zealand Herald | date=9 November 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref> He debuted for New Zealand alongside [[Matt Duffie]] and [[Tim Perry (rugby union)|Tim Perry]] against the [[Barbarian F.C.]] in November 2017, replacing [[Nathan Harris]] off the bench in the 67th minute.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://apnews.com/f10cc2201ed44225aa853fb3780ef7d8 | title=All Blacks beat Baa-baas 31-22 to begin European tour | work=Associated Press | date=5 November 2017  }}</ref> Aumua was denied a potential try due to a forward pass from Hurricanes team-mate [[Jeffery Toomaga-Allen]], but the All Blacks still managed to beat the Barbarians 31\u201322. He also replaced Harris off the bench 10 days later in a midweek game against a [[France national rugby union team|French XV]] selection, helping New Zealand win 28\u201323.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11944143 | title=Rugby: All Blacks dig in to deny French XV a famous win |agency = [[Associated Press]] | work=New Zealand Herald | date=15 November 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref> Because neither of those fixtures was [[Test match (rugby union)|tests]], Aumua would still await his test debut.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Rugby/all-blacks-add-5th-match-to-end-of-year-tour-20170719 | title=All Blacks add 5th match to end of year tour | work=Sport 24 | date=19 July 2017 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAumua made his debut for the Hurricanes, against the [[Canterbury region|Canterbury]]-based side the [[Crusaders (rugby union)|Crusaders]], on 10 March 2018 during round 4 of the [[2018 Super Rugby season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hurricanes.co.nz/news/article/hurricanes-squad-named-to-face-the-crusaders/ | title=HURRICANES SQUAD NAMED TO FACE THE CRUSADERS | work=Hurricanes | date=8 March 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Aumua replaced [[Ricky Riccitelli]] in the second half of the match, with the Hurricanes winning against the Crusaders 29\u201319.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/super-rugby/102159119/crusaders-toppled-by-an-energetic-and-muchimproved-hurricanes-side | title=Crusaders toppled by an energetic and much improved Hurricanes side | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=10 March 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Aumua performed well in all four of his 2018 Super Rugby appearances but was ruled out for the rest of the 2018 Super Rugby season due to a fractured wrist sustained against the [[Sharks (rugby union)|Sharks]] during a narrow 38\u201337 victory in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12038114 | title=Rugby: Asafo Aumua out for remainder of Super Rugby season with wrist injury | work=New Zealand Herald | date=23 April 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Aumua's rehabilitation period was scheduled for 12 weeks.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/super-rugby/103311054/hurricanes-hooker-asafo-aumua-set-for-12week-stint-on-the-sidelines | title=Hurricanes hooker Asafo Aumua set for 12-week stint on the sidelines | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=23 April 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing a wrist injury, Aumua appeared in Wellington's 31-man squad announcement after head coach Chris Gibbes released their premiership side in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mitre10cup.co.nz/News/32782/wellington-primed-for-premiership-run | title=Wellington primed for Premiership run | author=Lynn McConnell | work=Mitre 10 Cup | date=15 August 2018 | accessdate=31 October 2018 }}</ref> He made his return to play for Wellington in week one of the [[2018 Mitre 10 Cup]] competition against [[Otago Rugby Football Union|Otago]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mitre10cup.co.nz/News/32875/preview-wellington-v-otago | title=PREVIEW: Wellington v Otago | work=Mitre 10 Cup | date=18 August 2018 | accessdate=31 October 2018 }}</ref> At seasons-end Aumua appeared in their away semi-final, against Auckland and was re-called to the New Zealand squad to prepare for [[Japan national rugby union team|Japan]] in November for the [[2018 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2018 end of year tour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2018/10/all-blacks-asafo-aumua-ready-to-claim-second-chance.html | title=All Blacks: Asafo Aumua ready to claim second chance | author=Ollie Ritchie | work=Newshub | date=16 October 2018 | accessdate=23 October 2018 }}</ref> Aumua's re-call to the All Blacks unfortunately saw him fail to make the field, with Hurricanes Captain, [[Dane Coles]], returning from injury.\n\n=== 2019\u2013present ===\nAumua rejoined the Hurricanes squad for their upcoming season after head coach [[John Plumtree]] named his inclusion during the [[2019 Super Rugby season|2019 Super Rugby]] side announcement in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/nz-newspapers/central-north-island/sport/sport-region-6459/108215200/Salesi-Rayasi-returns-home-as-one-of-six-new-Hurricanes-for-2019 | title=Salesi Rayasi returns home as one of six new Hurricanes for 2019 | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=31 October 2018 | accessdate=31 October 2018 }}</ref> He made his first appearance of 2019 against the [[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] at [[FMG Stadium Waikato]] on 15 March.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/sport/rugby/ngani-laumape-play-50th-game-ben-lam-rested-hurricanes-clash-chiefs?variant=tb_v_1 | title=Ngani Laumape to play 50th game, Ben Lam rested for Hurricanes clash with Chiefs | work=1 News | date=13 March 2019 | accessdate=16 March 2019 }}</ref> Aumua picked up a concussion in the last minute of the Chiefs match and was rested for a week.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/super-rugby/111450728/hurricanes-make-10-changes-rest-dane-coles-tj-perenara-ngani-laumpape | title=Hurricanes make 10 changes, rest Dane Coles, TJ Perenara, Ngani Laumape | author=Liam Hyslop | work=Stuff | date=21 March 2019 | accessdate=23 March 2019 }}</ref> Dane Coles' ongoing run of injuries saw Aumua start in most games of the Super Rugby season, with Coles eventually returning to captain the team in the playoffs.<ref name=\"the-unlucky-five\">{{cite web | url=https://www.rugbypass.com/news/the-unlucky-five-where-did-the-five-dropped-all-blacks-go-wrong/| title= The Unlukcy Five: Where did the five dropped All Blacks go wrong? | author=Alex McLeod | work=RugbyPass | date=1 August 2019 | accessdate=25 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAumua played well throughout early 2019, displacing [[Nathan Harris]] from the New Zealand squad for the [[2019 Rugby Championship]]. Aumua, however, failed to make his test debut during the competition, with the form of [[Liam Coltman]] proving too strong. This saw Aumua as one of five players to be dropped, on 1 August, following a test against [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]].<ref name=the-unlucky-five/> After being released from international duties, Aumua missed the first-round match against [[Tasman Rugby Union|Tasman]] but returned as one of four changes that were named to play against [[Hawke's Bay Rugby Union|Hawke's Bay]] in [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] for the [[2019 Mitre 10 Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wrfu.co.nz/news/post/asafo-aumua-returns-to-lions-squad-to-face-hawkes-bay/| title= Asafo Aumua returns to Lions squad to face Hawke's Bay | work=Welligton Rugby Football Union | date=14 August 2019 | accessdate=15 March 2020 }}</ref> He scored a brace against [[Waikato Rugby Union|Waikato]] to help secure [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]] a home semi-final with a bonus-point win.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2019/10/mitre-10-cup-wellington-book-home-semi-final-with-bonus-point-win-over-waikato.html| title= Wellington book home semi-final with bonus-point win over Waikato | author=Luke Robinson | work=Newshub | date=12 October 2019 | accessdate=15 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!Club!!Year!!Competition!!{{Tooltip|GP|Games played}}!!{{Tooltip|GS|Games started}}!!{{Tooltip|TRY|Tries scored}}!!{{Tooltip|CON|Conversions scored}}!!{{Tooltip|PEN|Penalty goals scored}}!!{{Tooltip|DGL|Drop goals scored}}!!{{Tooltip|PTS|Total points scored}}!!{{Tooltip|WL%|Success percentage}}!!{{yel}}!!{{sent off}}\n|-\n|rowspan=4 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016 Mitre 10 Cup|2016]]\n|rowspan=4 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Mitre 10 Cup]]<br /><small>(incl. [[Ranfurly Shield]])</small>\n|10||2||6||0||0||0||30||50.00||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017 Mitre 10 Cup|2017]]\u2020\n|10||7||7||0||0||0||35||90.00||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018 Mitre 10 Cup|2018]]\n|11||9||4||0||0||0||20||54.55||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2019 Mitre 10 Cup|2019]]\n|11||11||2||0||0||0||10||72.73||0||0\n|-\n| colspan=13 style=\"background-color: #DDDDDD\" |\n|-\n|rowspan=3 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018 Super Rugby season|2018]]\n|rowspan=3 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Super Rugby]]\n|4||0||0||0||0||0||0||100.00||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2019 Super Rugby season|2019]]\n|11||5||0||0||0||0||0||72.73||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2020 Super Rugby season|2020]]\n|6||4||1||0||0||0||5||66.67<!---{{#expr:4/6*100 round 2}}--->||0||0\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" valign=\"top\"\n|colspan=3 style=\"text-align: center\"| '''Career'''\n|'''63'''||'''38'''||'''20'''||'''0'''||'''0'''||'''0'''||'''100'''||'''76.19<!---{{#expr:48/63*100 round 2}}--->'''||'''0'''||'''0'''\n|}\n<small>'''Updated:''' 13 March 2020</small>\n<small>'''Source:''' [https://www.rugbyhistory.co.nz/player/asafo-aumua Asafo J Aumua Rugby History]</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.allblacks.com/Player/AllBlacks?id=2516 Asafo Aumua] at [[All Blacks]].com\n* [http://www.itsrugby.co.uk/player-37785.html Asafo Aumua] at It'sRugby.co.uk\n\n{{Hurricanes squad}}\n{{Wellington Mitre 10 Cup squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aumua, Asafo}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Samoan descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union hookers]]\n[[Category:Rugby union players from Lower Hutt]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n|           name = Asafo Aumua\n|          image =\n|     image_size =\n|        caption =\n|       fullname = Asafo Junior Aumua\n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|05|05|df=y}}\n|    birth_place = [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], New Zealand\n|         height = {{convert|177|cm|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n|         weight = {{convert|108|kg|lb stlb|0|abbr=on}}\n|         school = [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St. Patrick's College Silverstream]]\n|     university =\n|      relatives =\n|     occupation =\n|         spouse =\n|       position = [[Hooker (rugby union)|Hooker]]\n|    currentclub = [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]], [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n|     allblackno = 1163\n|     allblackid = 1163\n|    youthyears1 =\n|    youthclubs1 =\n|         years1 = 2016\u2013\n|         clubs1 = [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]]\n|          apps1 = 42\n|        points1 = 95\n|         years2 = 2018\u2013\n|         clubs2 = [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n|          apps2 = 21\n|        points2 = 5\n|      repyears1 = 2016\u20132017\n|       repteam1 = [[New Zealand national under-20 rugby union team|New Zealand U20]]\n|       repcaps1 = 14\n|     reppoints1 = 35\n|      repyears2 = 2017\n|       repteam2 = [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]]\n|       repcaps2 = 2\n|     reppoints2 = 0\n|     clubupdate = 13 March 2020\n|      repupdate = 13 March 2020\n}}\n\n'''Asafo Junior Aumua''' ({{IPAc-en|a\u028a|\u02c8|m|u\u02d0|\u0259}}; born 5 May 1997) is a New Zealand professional [[rugby union]] footballer who plays as a [[Hooker (rugby union)|hooker]] for New Zealand franchise [[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]] and the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand national team]]. In his youth career, he was selected to play in the 2016 and 2017 [[World Rugby Under 20 Championship|World Rugby Under 20 Championships]] for [[New Zealand national under-20 rugby union team|New Zealand]] and took part in [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St. Patrick's College Silverstream]] first XV, the top representative team in secondary school.\n\nAumua represents the [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]] provincial team and made his [[Professional sport|professional]] debut for the union in 2016 at the age of 19. He spent two seasons at the [[Mitre 10 Cup]] side, before earning a place in the Hurricanes [[2018 Super Rugby season|2018 Super Rugby]] squad.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hurricanes.co.nz/news/article/hurricanes-2018-squad-announced/ | title=HURRICANES 2018 SQUAD ANNOUNCED | work=Hurricanes | date=1 November 2017 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> He won a championship with Wellington in 2017 and was named [[New Zealand Rugby Union|NZRU]] Age Grade Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/all-blacks/99875399/Sam-Whitelock-claims-player-of-the-year-as-Black-Ferns-grab-team-of-year-at-NZ-Rugby-Awards | title=Sam Whitelock claims player of the year as Black Ferns grab team of year at NZ Rugby Awards | work=Stuff | date=15 December 2017 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> He has scored 27 career [[Try (rugby)|tries]] in all competitions. Aumua made his senior international debut for New Zealand in November 2017 at the age of 20, becoming one of the [[List of New Zealand national rugby union team player records#Youngest players|youngest players]] to represent New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://stats.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/records/player/youngest_appearance.html?id=8;type=team | title=Youngest appearance | work=ESPN Scrum | date=3 August 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> He played in the [[2017 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2017 northern end-of-year tour]].\n\n== Early life ==\nAsafo Junior Aumua was born on 5 May 1997 in [[Wellington, New Zealand|Wellington]], the son of Tautua and Lisa Aumua.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/abs-squad/98146032/emotional-day-for-aumua-family-as-asafo-earns-his-first-on-his-all-blacks-callup | title=Emotional day for Aumua family as Asafo earns his first on his All Blacks callup | author=Liam Hyslop | work=Stuff | date=23 October 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> Growing up in [[Naenae]], he attended [[Naenae Intermediate School]] and [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St. Patrick's College Silverstream]].<ref name=\"new-all-black-asafo-aumua\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/all-blacks/98207504/big-things-have-been-predicted-for-new-all-black-asafo-aumua-from-a-young-age | title=Young All Blacks hooker Asafo Aumua tipped for stardom after meteoric rise | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=26 October 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> While at secondary school, Aumua was chosen to play for Silverstream first XV at the age of fifteen.<ref name=new-all-black-asafo-aumua/> He spent three years representing the side, winning two regional sevens titles and was a part of two unbeaten runs through the round robin of the [[Wellington Institute of Technology|WelTec]] premiership.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=2555 | title=Asafo Aumua - Hard work is more important than hype | author=Adam Julian | work=Club Rugby | date=15 August 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> In [[rugby sevens]], Aumua was named player of the tournament at the Marist College event, and joined the New Zealand Marist sevens squad for their tour of [[Samoa]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=1236 | title=St Pat?s Silverstream defend Marist College Sevens title | author=Adam Julian and Steven White | work=Club Rugby | date=8 February 2015 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> He primarily played hooker, but also played [[Centre (rugby union)|second five-eighth]], [[Prop (rugby union)|prop]], and [[Number 8 (rugby union)|number 8]] at first XV level.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=1808 | title=School leavers to watch in 2016 Wellington Premier rugby | author=Adam Julian and Steven White | work=Club Rugby | date=22 March 2016 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter his last year at Silverstream, Aumua was enrolled into the 26-man [[New Zealand Schoolboys|New Zealand Secondary Schools]] team for a three-match international series in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11513291 | title=Rugby: NZ Secondary Schools squad named | work=New Zealand Herald | date=15 September 2015 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> He was involved in a 24-point victory over [[Australian Schoolboys rugby union team|Australian Schoolboys]], where he scored a try that was recognized by [[Green and Gold Rugby]] journalist Nic Darveniza as try of the match, extending New Zealand's lead in the second half.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.greenandgoldrugby.com/nz-schools-give-aussies-a-masterclass/ | title=NZ Schools give Aussies a masterclass | author=Nic Darveniza | work=Green & Gold Rugby | date=2 October 2015 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> Aumua was one of six Wellington players to represent [[New Zealand national under-20 rugby union team|New Zealand]] at the World Rugby Under 20 Championships in [[Manchester]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allblacks.com/News/29146/nz-squad-named-for-world-rugby-under-20-championship | title=NZ squad named for World Rugby Under 20 Championship | work=All Blacks | date=10 May 2016 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> The following year, he was named to travel to [[Tbilisi]], in his second Under 20 World Championship campaign.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://rugbyheartland.co.nz/wp/2017/05/09/nz-under-20-squad-named-for-rugby-world-championship-in-georgia/ | title=NZ UNDER 20 SQUAD NAMED FOR RUGBY WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP IN GEORGIA | author=admin_hland | work=Rugby Heartland | date=9 May 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> New Zealand won their sixth title after defeating [[England national under-20 rugby union team|England]] 64\u201317 in a record score in a final, scoring ten tries to three.<ref name=\"win-world-rugby-championship\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11878903 | title=Rugby: New Zealand under-20s win World Rugby Championship in style | author=Campbell Burnes | work=New Zealand Herald | date=19 June 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> Aumua scored a [[Hat-trick#Rugby_football|hat-trick]], including one solo try in which he beat no less than six defenders.<ref name=win-world-rugby-championship/> He became only the second player to score a hat-trick in a final.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.worldrugby.org/u20/video/259852 | title=Asafo Aumua scores incredible hat-trick in World Rugby U20 Championship final | work=World Rugby | date=19 June 2017 | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\n=== 2016\u201318 ===\nDuring the [[2016 Mitre 10 Cup|2016 season]], at 19 years old, he made his first professional team debut when he came on as a reserve forward during the opening match against [[Hawke's Bay Rugby Union|Hawke's Bay]] at [[McLean Park]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/provincial/83321318/greg-foe-to-captain-wellington-against-hawkes-bay-as-brad-shields-recovers-from-injury | title=Greg Foe to captain Wellington against Hawke's Bay as Brad Shields recovers from injury | author=Liam Hyslop | work=Stuff | date=19 August 2016 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref> Representing the Wellington under-19 team in [[Taupo]], Aumua was ordered back after [[Leni Apisai]] failed concussion protocols in preparation against [[Northland Rugby Union|Northland]].<ref name=\"asafo-Aumua-came-as-no-surprise\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/rugby-world-cup/84594057/The-performance-of-Wellington-hooker-Asafo-Aumua-came-as-no-surprise-to-some | title=The performance of Wellington hooker Asafo Aumua came as no surprise to some | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=23 September 2016 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref> He scored three tries in the fixture, making him just the fourth hooker to register a hat-trick in the competition's history.<ref name=asafo-Aumua-came-as-no-surprise/> Aumua was the sides leading try-scorer with six in 10 games.<ref name=\"aumua-strong-contender\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/all-blacks/96436634/Wellington-sensation-Asafo-Aumua-strong-contender-for-All-Blacks-apprentice-role | title=Wellington sensation Asafo Aumua strong contender for All Blacks apprentice role | author=Marc Hinton | work=Stuff | date=2 September 2017 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nHis performance at national age grade level in 2017 impressed Wellington head coach Chris Gibbes ahead of the [[2017 Mitre 10 Cup]], and he was subsequently renamed in the squad for their upcoming season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clubrugby.co.nz/wellington/story.php?id=2550 | title=New caps in Wellington Lions squad for 2017 | work=Club Rugby | date=11 August 2017 | accessdate=16 July 2018 }}</ref> Aumua started well for Wellington, scoring three tries through the first three games of the competition.<ref name=aumua-strong-contender/> His scoring ability was noted after beating [[Outside backs (rugby union)|outside back]] defender [[George Bridge]] for a {{convert|60|m|yd|abbr=off}} solo try.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rugbydump.com/2017/09/5895/wellington-hooker-asafo-aumua-steps-fullback-to-score-incredible-60m-try | title=Wellington Hooker Asafo Aumua steps fullback to score incredible 60m try | work=Rugby Dump | date=18 September 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref> It saw Aumua place fourth-equal in the overall leading try-scorers with fellow [[Rugby union positions|front rower]] and teammate, [[Alex Fidow]] on seven tries each.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mitre10cup.co.nz/News/31619/statchat-the-leading-players-in-the-mitre-10-cup | title=STATCHAT: The leading players in the Mitre 10 Cup | work=Mitre 10 Cup | date=16 October 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing his 2017 provincial campaign, Aumua was called up into the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] for the [[2017 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2017 end of year tour]] despite the fact that he had not even made his [[Super Rugby]] debut.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11941981 | title=Rugby: Asafo Aumua has joined an elite but largely unhappy All Blacks club | work=New Zealand Herald | date=9 November 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref> He debuted for New Zealand alongside [[Matt Duffie]] and [[Tim Perry (rugby union)|Tim Perry]] against the [[Barbarian F.C.]] in November 2017, replacing [[Nathan Harris]] off the bench in the 67th minute.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://apnews.com/f10cc2201ed44225aa853fb3780ef7d8 | title=All Blacks beat Baa-baas 31-22 to begin European tour | work=Associated Press | date=5 November 2017  }}</ref> Aumua was denied a potential try due to a forward pass from Hurricanes team-mate [[Jeffery Toomaga-Allen]], but the All Blacks still managed to beat the Barbarians 31\u201322. He also replaced Harris off the bench 10 days later in a midweek game against a [[France national rugby union team|French XV]] selection, helping New Zealand win 28\u201323.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11944143 | title=Rugby: All Blacks dig in to deny French XV a famous win |agency = [[Associated Press]] | work=New Zealand Herald | date=15 November 2017 | accessdate=23 July 2018 }}</ref> Because neither of those fixtures was [[Test match (rugby union)|tests]], Aumua would still await his test debut.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Rugby/all-blacks-add-5th-match-to-end-of-year-tour-20170719 | title=All Blacks add 5th match to end of year tour | work=Sport 24 | date=19 July 2017 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAumua made his debut for the Hurricanes, against the [[Canterbury region|Canterbury]]-based side the [[Crusaders (rugby union)|Crusaders]], on 10 March 2018 during round 4 of the [[2018 Super Rugby season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hurricanes.co.nz/news/article/hurricanes-squad-named-to-face-the-crusaders/ | title=HURRICANES SQUAD NAMED TO FACE THE CRUSADERS | work=Hurricanes | date=8 March 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Aumua replaced [[Ricky Riccitelli]] in the second half of the match, with the Hurricanes winning against the Crusaders 29\u201319.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/super-rugby/102159119/crusaders-toppled-by-an-energetic-and-muchimproved-hurricanes-side | title=Crusaders toppled by an energetic and much improved Hurricanes side | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=10 March 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Aumua performed well in all four of his 2018 Super Rugby appearances but was ruled out for the rest of the 2018 Super Rugby season due to a fractured wrist sustained against the [[Sharks (rugby union)|Sharks]] during a narrow 38\u201337 victory in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12038114 | title=Rugby: Asafo Aumua out for remainder of Super Rugby season with wrist injury | work=New Zealand Herald | date=23 April 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref> Aumua's rehabilitation period was scheduled for 12 weeks.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/super-rugby/103311054/hurricanes-hooker-asafo-aumua-set-for-12week-stint-on-the-sidelines | title=Hurricanes hooker Asafo Aumua set for 12-week stint on the sidelines | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=23 April 2018 | accessdate=3 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing a wrist injury, Aumua appeared in Wellington's 31-man squad announcement after head coach Chris Gibbes released their premiership side in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mitre10cup.co.nz/News/32782/wellington-primed-for-premiership-run | title=Wellington primed for Premiership run | author=Lynn McConnell | work=Mitre 10 Cup | date=15 August 2018 | accessdate=31 October 2018 }}</ref> He made his return to play for Wellington in week one of the [[2018 Mitre 10 Cup]] competition against [[Otago Rugby Football Union|Otago]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mitre10cup.co.nz/News/32875/preview-wellington-v-otago | title=PREVIEW: Wellington v Otago | work=Mitre 10 Cup | date=18 August 2018 | accessdate=31 October 2018 }}</ref> At seasons-end Aumua appeared in their away semi-final, against Auckland and was re-called to the New Zealand squad to prepare for [[Japan national rugby union team|Japan]] in November for the [[2018 end-of-year rugby union internationals|2018 end of year tour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2018/10/all-blacks-asafo-aumua-ready-to-claim-second-chance.html | title=All Blacks: Asafo Aumua ready to claim second chance | author=Ollie Ritchie | work=Newshub | date=16 October 2018 | accessdate=23 October 2018 }}</ref> Aumua's re-call to the All Blacks unfortunately saw him fail to make the field, with Hurricanes Captain, [[Dane Coles]], returning from injury.\n\n=== 2019\u2013present ===\nAumua rejoined the Hurricanes squad for their upcoming season after head coach [[John Plumtree]] named his inclusion during the [[2019 Super Rugby season|2019 Super Rugby]] side announcement in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/nz-newspapers/central-north-island/sport/sport-region-6459/108215200/Salesi-Rayasi-returns-home-as-one-of-six-new-Hurricanes-for-2019 | title=Salesi Rayasi returns home as one of six new Hurricanes for 2019 | author=Hamish Bidwell | work=Stuff | date=31 October 2018 | accessdate=31 October 2018 }}</ref> He made his first appearance of 2019 against the [[Chiefs (rugby union)|Chiefs]] at [[FMG Stadium Waikato]] on 15 March.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/sport/rugby/ngani-laumape-play-50th-game-ben-lam-rested-hurricanes-clash-chiefs?variant=tb_v_1 | title=Ngani Laumape to play 50th game, Ben Lam rested for Hurricanes clash with Chiefs | work=1 News | date=13 March 2019 | accessdate=16 March 2019 }}</ref> Aumua picked up a concussion in the last minute of the Chiefs match and was rested for a week.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/super-rugby/111450728/hurricanes-make-10-changes-rest-dane-coles-tj-perenara-ngani-laumpape | title=Hurricanes make 10 changes, rest Dane Coles, TJ Perenara, Ngani Laumape | author=Liam Hyslop | work=Stuff | date=21 March 2019 | accessdate=23 March 2019 }}</ref> Dane Coles' ongoing run of injuries saw Aumua start in most games of the Super Rugby season, with Coles eventually returning to captain the team in the playoffs.<ref name=\"the-unlucky-five\">{{cite web | url=https://www.rugbypass.com/news/the-unlucky-five-where-did-the-five-dropped-all-blacks-go-wrong/| title= The Unlukcy Five: Where did the five dropped All Blacks go wrong? | author=Alex McLeod | work=RugbyPass | date=1 August 2019 | accessdate=25 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAumua played well throughout early 2019, displacing [[Nathan Harris]] from the New Zealand squad for the [[2019 Rugby Championship]]. Aumua, however, failed to make his test debut during the competition, with the form of [[Liam Coltman]] proving too strong. This saw Aumua as one of five players to be dropped, on 1 August, following a test against [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]].<ref name=the-unlucky-five/> After being released from international duties, Aumua missed the first-round match against [[Tasman Rugby Union|Tasman]] but returned as one of four changes that were named to play against [[Hawke's Bay Rugby Union|Hawke's Bay]] in [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] for the [[2019 Mitre 10 Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wrfu.co.nz/news/post/asafo-aumua-returns-to-lions-squad-to-face-hawkes-bay/| title= Asafo Aumua returns to Lions squad to face Hawke's Bay | work=Welligton Rugby Football Union | date=14 August 2019 | accessdate=15 March 2020 }}</ref> He scored a brace against [[Waikato Rugby Union|Waikato]] to help secure [[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]] a home semi-final with a bonus-point win.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2019/10/mitre-10-cup-wellington-book-home-semi-final-with-bonus-point-win-over-waikato.html| title= Wellington book home semi-final with bonus-point win over Waikato | author=Luke Robinson | work=Newshub | date=12 October 2019 | accessdate=15 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!Club!!Year!!Competition!!{{Tooltip|GP|Games played}}!!{{Tooltip|GS|Games started}}!!{{Tooltip|TRY|Tries scored}}!!{{Tooltip|CON|Conversions scored}}!!{{Tooltip|PEN|Penalty goals scored}}!!{{Tooltip|DGL|Drop goals scored}}!!{{Tooltip|PTS|Total points scored}}!!{{Tooltip|WL%|Success percentage}}!!{{yel}}!!{{sent off}}\n|-\n|rowspan=4 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Wellington Rugby Football Union|Wellington]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016 Mitre 10 Cup|2016]]\n|rowspan=4 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Mitre 10 Cup]]<br /><small>(incl. [[Ranfurly Shield]])</small>\n|10||2||6||0||0||0||30||50.00||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017 Mitre 10 Cup|2017]]\u2020\n|10||7||7||0||0||0||35||90.00||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018 Mitre 10 Cup|2018]]\n|11||9||4||0||0||0||20||54.55||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2019 Mitre 10 Cup|2019]]\n|11||11||2||0||0||0||10||72.73||0||0\n|-\n| colspan=13 style=\"background-color: #DDDDDD\" |\n|-\n|rowspan=3 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Hurricanes (rugby union)|Hurricanes]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018 Super Rugby season|2018]]\n|rowspan=3 style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Super Rugby]]\n|4||0||0||0||0||0||0||100.00||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2019 Super Rugby season|2019]]\n|11||5||0||0||0||0||0||72.73||0||0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2020 Super Rugby season|2020]]\n|6||4||1||0||0||0||5||66.67<!---{{#expr:4/6*100 round 2}}--->||0||0\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" valign=\"top\"\n|colspan=3 style=\"text-align: center\"| '''Career'''\n|'''63'''||'''38'''||'''20'''||'''0'''||'''0'''||'''0'''||'''100'''||'''76.19<!---{{#expr:48/63*100 round 2}}--->'''||'''0'''||'''0'''\n|}\n<small>'''Updated:''' 13 March 2020</smal