i.edu/publications/killing-qassem-soleimani-was-there-better-way The killing of Qassem Soleimani: Was there a better way?]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Iran\u2013United States relations}}\n{{Trump presidency}}\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Aviation|Iran|Iraq|Modern history|United States|War}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baghdad international airport attack, 2020}}\n[[Category:21st century in Baghdad]]\n[[Category:21st-century military history of the United States]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis]]\n[[Category:2020 airstrikes]]\n[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020 controversies]]\n[[Category:2020 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Assassinations in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Attacks in Asia in 2020]]\n[[Category:Attacks in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Drone strikes conducted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Drone strikes in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States proxy conflict]]\n[[Category:Iraq\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Military assassinations]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Qasem Soleimani]]\n[[Category:Targeted killing in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|U.S. dronestrike killing of Iranian Gen. Qasem Soleimani}}\n{{Infobox military operation\n |name          = 2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike\n |partof        = the [[American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|American-led intervention in Iraq]] and the [[2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|Persian Gulf crisis]]\n |image         = File:Bombing at Baghdad Airport 2020.png\n |image_upright = \n |alt           = \n |caption       = The explosion from the airstrike, as seen from a nearby suburb.\n |scope         = \n |type          = [[Drone strike]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/02/middleeast/baghdad-airport-rockets/index.html |title=US drone strike ordered by Trump kills top Iranian commander in Baghdad |last=Cohen |first=Zachary |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103031258/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/02/middleeast/baghdad-airport-rockets/index.html |archive-date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Alkhshali |first2=Hamdi |last3=Khadder |first3=Kareem |last4=Dewan |first4=Angela}}</ref>\n |location      = Near [[Baghdad Airport Road]], [[Baghdad International Airport]], [[Baghdad Governorate]], [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]]\n |coordinates   = {{Coord|33|15|29|N|44|15|22|E|region:IQ-BG_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n |map_type      = Iraq\n |map_size      = \n |map_caption   = Location in Iraq\n |map_label     = \n |commanded_by  = \n |target        = [[Qasem Soleimani]]<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n |date          = {{Start date|df=y|2020|1|3}}\n |time          = About 1:00{{nbsp}}a.m.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2020/01/qassem-soleimani-death-missed/604396/ |title=Qassem Soleimani Haunted the Arab World |last=Ghattas |first=Kim |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103215246/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2020/01/qassem-soleimani-death-missed/604396/ |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n |time-begin    = \n |time-end      = \n |timezone      = [[Time in Iraq|local time]], [[UTC+03:00|UTC+3]]\n |outcome       = See ''[[#Aftermath|Aftermath]]''\n |casualties    = 10 killed, including [[Qasem Soleimani]] and [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]]\n |injuries      = \n |campaignbox   = {{Campaignbox 2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis}}{{Campaignbox Iraqi insurgency (2017\u2013present)}}\n|title=|conflict=}}\n{{Donald Trump series}}\n\nOn 3 January 2020, a United States [[drone strike]] near [[Baghdad International Airport]] [[targeted killing|targeted and killed]] Iranian major general [[Qasem Soleimani]] of Iran's [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC) while he was planned to meet Iraqi PM [[Adil Abdul-Mahdi]] in Baghdad. Soleimani was commander of the [[Quds Force]]\u2014which has been designated a terrorist organization by the U.S., [[Canada]], [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Bahrain]]\u2014and was considered the second most powerful person of Iran, subordinate to [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] [[Ali Khamenei]]. Nine others were killed alongside Soleimani, including Iranian and [[Iraq]]i nationals such as deputy chairman of Iraq's [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] (PMF) and commander of the Iran-backed [[Kata'ib Hezbollah]] militia, [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]]\u2014a designated terrorist in the U.S. and in the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE).\n\nThe strike occurred during the [[2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis]], which began after the U.S. [[United States withdrawal from the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|withdrew from the 2015 nuclear deal with Iran]] in 2018, reimposed [[United States sanctions against Iran|sanctions]], and accused Iranian elements of fomenting a campaign to harass U.S. forces in the region. On 27 December 2019, the [[K-1 Air Base]] in Iraq, which hosts Iraqi and U.S. personnel, was [[2019 K-1 Air Base attack|attacked]], killing an American contractor. The U.S. responded by launching [[December 2019 United States airstrikes in Iraq and Syria|airstrikes across Iraq and Syria]], killing 25 Kata'ib Hezbollah militiamen. Days later, Shia militiamen and their supporters retaliated by [[Attack on the United States embassy in Baghdad|attacking the U.S. embassy]] in the [[Green Zone]].\n\nU.S. officials justified the strike claiming it was necessary to stop an \"imminent attack\", though later clarifying the legal justification of the action as being taken \"in response to an escalating series of attacks...to protect United States personnel, to deter Iran from conducting or supporting further attacks...and to end Iran's strategic escalation of attacks...\" <ref>https://www.lawfareblog.com/white-house-releases-report-justifying-soleimani-strike</ref> Some critics of the strike questioned the legality of the attack with respect to [[international law]], as well as the domestic laws of the U.S. Iran called the strike an act of \"[[state terrorism]]\". The Iraqi government said the attack undermined its national sovereignty and considered it a breach of its bilateral security agreements with the U.S. and an act of aggression against its officials. On 5{{nbsp}}January 2020, the [[Iraqi parliament]] passed a non-binding resolution to expel all foreign troops from its territory while, on the same day, Iran took the fifth and last step of reducing commitments to the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|2015 international nuclear deal]].\n\nSoleimani's killing sharply escalated tensions between the U.S. and Iran and stoked fears of a military conflict. Iranian leaders vowed revenge, while U.S. officials said they would [[Preemptive war|preemptively]] attack any Iran-backed paramilitary groups in Iraq that they perceived as a threat. Many in the international community reacted with concern and issued statements or declarations urging restraint and diplomacy. Five days after the airstrike, Iran launched a series of [[2020 Iranian attack on U.S. forces in Iraq|missile attacks on U.S. forces based in Iraq]], the first direct engagement between Iran and the U.S. since [[Operation Praying Mantis]] in 1988. Following the shootdown of [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] amidst the escalation, leaders from both countries seemed reluctant to further escalate the crisis.\n\n== Background ==\n\n{{Further|2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|Iran\u2013United States relations}}\n\n=== Assassination as a policy consideration ===\n\nThe modern Middle East has seen a number of occasions in which the assassination of high-level government and military figures was attempted, or at least considered. Such instances include attempts by the United States to target during air raids Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] in 1986 and Iraqi leader [[Saddam Hussein]] in 1991, 1998, and 2003, and in addition to successful missions to kill non-state terrorist leaders such as [[Osama bin Laden]], [[Anwar al-Awlaki]] and [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]].<ref name=\"Schilling\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.psqonline.org/article.cfm?IDArticle=19545 | title=Decision Making in Using Assassinations in International Relations | journal=[[Political Science Quarterly]] | volume=131 | issue=3 | date=Fall 2016 | pages=503\u2013539 | last=Schilling | first=Warner R. | last2=Schilling | first2=Jonathan L. | doi=10.1002/polq.12487 | access-date=24 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019023015/http://www.psqonline.org/article.cfm?IDArticle=19545 | archive-date=19 October 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Over the past centuries there has largely been a norm against governments conducting assassinations of foreign leaders, but that norm has been weakening over time, especially since World War II.<ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite journal | first=Ward | last=Thomas | title=Norms and Security: The Case of International Assassination | journal=[[International Security]] | volume=25 | issue=1 | date=Summer 2000 | pages= 105\u2013133|jstor = 2626775|doi = 10.1162/016228800560408}}</ref> The effectiveness of anti-terrorist \"leadership targeting\" has become a subject of scholarly debate, especially with regard to whether such killings are actually beneficial to a country's foreign policy goals.<ref>For the leading proponent of the view that leadership targeting is not effective, see {{cite book | title=Leadership Decapitation: Strategic Targeting of Terrorist Organizations | first=Jenna | last=Jordan | publisher=Stanford University Press | date=2019 | isbn= 978-1-5036-0824-5}}. For arguments that such targeting does work, see {{cite journal | first=Bryan C. | last=Price | title=Targeting Top Terrorists: How Leadership Decapitation Contributes to Counterterrorism | journal=[[International Security]] | volume=36 | issue=4 |date=Spring 2012 | pages= 9\u201346 | jstor=41428119| doi=10.1162/ISEC_a_00075}}; and {{cite journal | first=Patrick B. | last=Johnston | title=Does Decapitation Work? Assessing the Effectiveness of Leadership Targeting in Counterinsurgency Campaigns | journal=[[International Security]] | volume= 36 | issue=4 | date=Spring 2012 | pages= 47\u201379 | jstor=41428120 | doi=10.1162/ISEC_a_00076}}</ref> Both the consideration against further eroding norms and the questions regarding effectiveness would be raised in the wake of the strike against Soleimani.<ref name=\"Walt\">{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/03/qassem-suleimani-trump-iran-policy-lacks-coherent-objectives-strategy/ | title=Trump's Iran Policy Is Brain-Dead | author-first=Stephen M. | author-last=Walt | magazine=[[Foreign Policy]] | date=3 January 2020 | access-date=16 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116023907/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/01/03/qassem-suleimani-trump-iran-policy-lacks-coherent-objectives-strategy/ | archive-date=16 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The costs and benefits of foreign policy assassinations are difficult to compute, and decisions to go ahead with such actions often reflect the vague, and not always realized, hope that any successor to the targeted person will be less capable against, or will embody policies more favorable toward, the country taking the action.<ref name=\"Schilling\" />\n\n=== U.S. and Iranian activities in Iraq since 2014 ===\n\n{{Further|American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|Iranian intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)}}\n\nIn 2014, the U.S. intervened in Iraq, as a part of [[Operation Inherent Resolve]] (OIR), an American-led mission to degrade and fight the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) terror organization, and have been training and operating alongside Iraqi forces as a part of the anti-ISIL coalition. In 2017, ISIL was largely defeated back from Iraq during the [[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|three-year battle]], with the help of primarily Iran-backed [[Shia Islam|Shia]] militias\u2014[[Popular Mobilization Forces]], reporting to the [[Prime Minister of Iraq|Iraqi prime minister]] since 2016\u2014and the U.S.-backed [[Iraqi Armed Forces]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.euronews.com/2018/08/31/exclusive-iran-moves-missiles-to-iraq-in-warning-to-enemies-sources |title=Iran moves missiles to Iraq in warning to enemies\u2014sources |date=31 August 2018 |website=[[Euronews]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101100301/https://www.euronews.com/2018/08/31/exclusive-iran-moves-missiles-to-iraq-in-warning-to-enemies-sources |archive-date=1 January 2020 |access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Political considerations ===\n\nConcerning the provisional nuclear deal with Iran, some critics of the treaty condemned that Iran could make a [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear bomb]] after expiry of the limited-term nuclear deal.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Sick |first=Gary G. |date=7 September 2015 |title=Iran After the Deal\u2014What to Do When the JCPOA Expires |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/iran/2015-09-07/iran-after-deal |journal=Foreign Affairs |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714045317/https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/iran/2015-09-07/iran-after-deal |archive-date=14 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> President Trump also criticized the 15-year nuclear deal with Iran by the previous U.S. administration's paying $1.7&nbsp;billion cash to Tehran.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2018/03/01/was-obamas-1-7-billion-cash-deal-with-iran-prohibited-by-u-s-law/ |title=Analysis &#124; Was Obama's $1.7&nbsp;billion cash deal with Iran prohibited by U.S. law? |last=CheckerEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow |first=Glenn Kessler closeGlenn KesslerThe Fact |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122173757/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2018/03/01/was-obamas-1-7-billion-cash-deal-with-iran-prohibited-by-u-s-law/ |archive-date=22 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/14/us/politics/trump-iran-credibility.html |title=As Trump Accuses Iran, He Has One Problem: His Own Credibility |last=Baker |first=Peter |date=14 June 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190915124406/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/14/us/politics/trump-iran-credibility.html |archive-date=15 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/trump-maximum-pressure-strategy-iran-fail-190916092330241.html |title=Trump's strategy against Iran can still succeed |last=Bakeer |first=Ali |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215201637/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/trump-maximum-pressure-strategy-iran-fail-190916092330241.html |archive-date=15 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tensions rose between Iran and the U.S. in 2018 after Trump unilaterally withdrew from the 2015 nuclear deal and reimposed [[United States sanctions against Iran|sanctions against Iran]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2058931/iraq-condemns-us-air-strikes-unacceptable-and-dangerous |title=Iraq Condemns US Air Strikes as Unacceptable and Dangerous |date=30 December 2019 |website=[[Asharq Al-Awsat]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230232420/https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2058931/iraq-condemns-us-air-strikes-unacceptable-and-dangerous |archive-date=30 December 2019 |access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref> which severely affected Iran's economy,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-48011496 |title=Iran oil: US to end sanctions exemptions for major importers |date=22 April 2019 |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201190246/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-48011496 |archive-date=1 December 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> as a part of the U.S. administration's strategy of applying \"maximum pressure\" against Iran for the purpose of establishment of the new Iran\u2013U.S. nuclear deal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/deal-iran-year-191231073235120.html |title=Can there be a deal between Iran and the US in the new year? |last=Mousavian |first=Seyed Hossein |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106082149/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/deal-iran-year-191231073235120.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/06/bolton-keeps-trying-goad-iran-war/592108/ |title=Bolton Keeps Trying to Goad Iran into War |last=Beinart |first=Peter |date=20 June 2019 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105210406/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/06/bolton-keeps-trying-goad-iran-war/592108/ |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2020/01/10/soleimani-death-iran-revenge-u-s-navy-target/2822463001/ |title=Iran got its revenge for Qasem Soleimani's killing but the US Navy is still a target |date=10 January 2020 |website=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Quds Force which Soleimani led has been designated a terrorist organization by Canada,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx |title=Currently listed entities |website=Publicsafety.gc.ca |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202121931/https://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx |archive-date=2 February 2017 |access-date=11 November 2014}}</ref> Saudi Arabia, Bahrain,<ref>[https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/saudi-bahrain-add-irans-irgc-to-terror-lists-spa Saudi, Bahrain add Iran's IRGC to terror lists\u2014SPA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510040315/https://www.euronews.com/2018/10/23/saudi-bahrain-add-irans-irgc-to-terror-lists-spa |date=10 May 2019}} euronews.com</ref> and the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/hp644.aspx |title=Fact Sheet: Designation of Iranian Entities and Individuals for Proliferation Activities and Support for Terrorism |date=25 October 2007 |publisher=U.S. Department of the Treasury |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110014318/http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/hp644.aspx |archive-date=10 November 2014 |access-date=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/2019/04/08/710987393/u-s-labels-irans-revolutionary-guard-as-a-foreign-terrorist-organization U.S. Labels Iran's Revolutionary Guard As A Foreign Terrorist Organization] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610123914/https://www.npr.org/2019/04/08/710987393/u-s-labels-irans-revolutionary-guard-as-a-foreign-terrorist-organization |date=10 June 2019}} NPR</ref> Soleimani himself was sanctioned by the United Nations<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/profile-who-is-qasem-soleimani-/1690827 |title=PROFILE\u2014Who is Qasem Soleimani? |last=Ali H. M. Abo Rezeg |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104171212/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/profile-who-is-qasem-soleimani-/1690827 |archive-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]] |quote=He was among the Iranian individuals who were sanctioned by the UN Security Council resolution 1747}}</ref> and sanctioned by the [[European Union]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2012:165:0072:01:EN:HTML |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130213132209/http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2012:165:0072:01:EN:HTML |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 February 2013 |title=EUR-Lex\u201432012D0333\u2014EN |date=13 February 2013 |website=archive.ph}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2012:165:0072:0074:EN:PDF |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214070453/https://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2012:165:0072:0074:EN:PDF |archive-date=14 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/profile-who-is-qasem-soleimani-/1690827 |title=PROFILE\u2014Who is Qasem Soleimani? |last=Ali H. M. Abo Rezeg |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104171212/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/profile-who-is-qasem-soleimani-/1690827 |archive-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]] |quote=on 24 June 2011, an official statement by the European Union said that European sanctions were imposed on three Iranian commanders of the Revolutionary Guards including Soleimani.}}</ref> and was on U.S. terror watchlists.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2008/03/31/32141/iranian-who-brokered-iraqi-peace.html |title=Iranian who brokered Iraqi peace is on U.S. terrorist watch list &#124; McClatchy |date=29 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929065353/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2008/03/31/32141/iranian-who-brokered-iraqi-peace.html |archive-date=29 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]] was designated a terrorist by the U.S. in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg195.aspx |title=Treasury Designates Individual, Entity Posing Threat to Stability in Iraq |website=treasury.gov |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107021240/https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg195.aspx |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The 25,000-strong militia he commanded,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/.premium-abu-mahdi-al-muhandis-iran-kataib-hezbollah-qassem-soleimani-u-s-strike-iraq-syria-israel-1.8344495 |title=Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis, Head of pro-Iranian Kataib Hezbollah Targeted by U.S. |last=Melman |first=Yossi |date=3 January 2020 |via=Haaretz |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107161808/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/.premium-abu-mahdi-al-muhandis-iran-kataib-hezbollah-qassem-soleimani-u-s-strike-iraq-syria-israel-1.8344495 |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Kata'ib Hezbollah, is considered a terrorist organization by [[Japan]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/ME_N-africa/KH.html |title=\u30ab\u30bf\u30a4\u30d6\u30fb\u30d2\u30ba\u30dc\u30e9\uff08KH\uff09 &#124; \u56fd\u969b\u30c6\u30ed\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u8981\u89a7\uff08Web\u7248\uff09 &#124; \u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5e81 |date=2 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302123316/http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/ME_N-africa/KH.html |archive-date=2 March 2019}}</ref> the [[United Arab Emirates]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wam.ae/ar/news/emirates-arab-international/1395272465559.html |title=\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0632\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u064a\u0639\u062a\u0645\u062f \u0642\u0627\u0626\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0646\u0638\u064a\u0645\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0631\u0647\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629. &#124; WAM |date=17 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117230142/http://www.wam.ae/ar/news/emirates-arab-international/1395272465559.html |archive-date=17 November 2014}}</ref> and the U.S.<ref name=\"Lawrence\">{{Cite web |url=http://understandingwar.org/backgrounder/iraq-situation-report-may-23-25-2015 |title=Iraq Situation Report: May 23\u201325, 2015 |last=Lawrence |first=John |date=26 May 2015 |website=understandingwar.org |publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]] |access-date=27 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527225937/http://understandingwar.org/backgrounder/iraq-situation-report-may-23-25-2015 |archive-date=27 May 2015 |url-status=live }} See paragraph 5 of the report.</ref>\n\n=== Importance of the assassination of Soleimani ===\n\nGeneral [[Qasem Soleimani]] was considered the second most powerful person in [[Iran]], behind Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] [[Ayatollah]] [[Ali Khamenei]],<ref name=\"nrc3Jan\">{{in lang|nl}} [https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2020/01/03/vs-doden-topgeneraal-iran-vrees-voor-escalatie-groeit-a3985625#/handelsblad/2020/01/03/#101 'VS doden topgeneraal Iran, vrees voor escalatie groeit' (US kill top general Iran, fear for escalation grows)]. ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 3{{nbsp}}January 2020. Retrieved 10 January 2020.</ref> and in his later years enjoyed a near unassailable heroic status, especially with supporters of [[Tehran]]'s hard-line politics.<ref name=nrc3print4Jan />\n\nEver since the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]] (1980\u201388), in which Iran felt attacked not only by [[Saddam Hussein]]'s Iraq but by the whole world siding with Saddam against Ayatollah [[Ruhollah Khomeini]]'s [[Islamic republic]] in Tehran,<ref name=\"Roelants\">Carolien Roelants, Iran expert of ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', in a debate on ''[[Buitenhof (TV series)|Buitenhof]]'' on Dutch television, 5 January 2020.</ref> with notably the U.S. supplying weapons and intelligence to Iraq,<ref name=\"nrc6Jan\">{{in lang|nl}} [https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2020/01/06/30937012-a3985804#/handelsblad/2020/01/06/#104 'Het conflict tussen Iran en de VS in vogelvlucht' (The conflict between Iran and the US in a nutshell)]. ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 6 January 2020. Retrieved 10 January 2020.</ref> Soleimani had developed into the architect of all of Iran's foreign policies in the Middle East until Afghanistan<ref name=nrc3Jan /><ref name=\"nrc3print4Jan\">{{in lang|nl}} [https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2020/01/03/soleimani-had-een-heldenstatus-in-iran-hij-maakte-het-land-machtiger-a3985662#/handelsblad/2020/01/04/#104 'Soleimani had een heldenstatus in Iran, hij maakte het land machtiger' (Soleimani had a heroic status in Iran, he made the country mightier)]. 3 January 2020. Retrieved 10 January 2020.</ref><ref name=\"nrc3Jan,pg.3\">{{in lang|nl}} [https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2020/01/03/einde-invloed-vs-in-irak-nabij-a3985626#/handelsblad/2020/01/03/#102 'Na aanval op Soleimani lijkt einde invloed VS in Iraq nabij' (After attack on Soleimani, US influence in Iraq seems nearly ended)]. ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'', 3 January 2020. Retrieved 10 January 2020.</ref>{{clarify|reason=What does \"the Middle East until Afghanistan\" mean?|date=January 2020}} and a key figure in all of Iran's foreign and defence policies.<ref name=nrc3Jan /> He provided crucial support to President [[Bashar al-Assad]]'s regime during the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/5597ff0f046a67805cc233d5933a53ed |title=US kills Iran's most powerful general in Baghdad airstrike |date=2 January 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103023408/https://apnews.com/5597ff0f046a67805cc233d5933a53ed |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He even wrote U.S. General [[David Petraeus]], then [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq#Commanders|Commander]] of the [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq|Multi-National Force in Iraq]], a letter in early 2008 to tell him: \"General Petraeus, you must know that I, Qasem Soleimani, am in charge of the Iranian policies concerning Iraq, [[Lebanon]], [[Gaza Strip|Gaza]] and [[Afghanistan]]\".<ref name=nrc3print4Jan />\n\nThat made his killing by the U.S. on 3 January 2020 a significant aggravation<ref name=Roelants /> of the [[Iran\u2013United States relations|existing tensions]] between the U.S. and Iran, distrusted and disliked by U.S. leaders as recently testified by the [[Countering America's Adversaries Through Sanctions Act]] of 2017 and further [[Foreign policy of the Donald Trump administration#Iran|policy of President Trump]]. Iran's leaders the days after the assassination of Soleimani vowed \"shattering revenge\"<ref name=nrc3Jan /> \"on places and at times where the U.S. don't expect it\".<ref>Several tv news bulletins, 3\u20137 Jan 2020.</ref>\n\n=== Prior threats against Qasem Soleimani ===\n\nFormer U.S. presidents<!-- it's either an honorific (capitalized) or a job (\"us\" is the boss)\u2014not both. --> [[George W. Bush]] and [[Barack Obama]] both considered and rejected targeting Qasem Soleimani, reasoning that it would escalate to a full-scale war. Retired CIA officer Marc Polymeropoulos told ''[[The New York Times]]'' that Soleimani, unlike other adversaries killed by the U.S., felt comfortable operating in the open and was not hard to find. He often took photographs of himself and openly taunted U.S. forces.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/nation-world/ct-nw-nyt-qassem-soleimani-iran-20200103-6cfuwdo5cfhi7aocmrhn75nbse-story.html |title=Iran's Maj. Gen. Qassem Soleimani traveled with impunity\u2014until U.S. drones found him |last=Schmitt |first=Eric |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |agency=The New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103193635/https://www.chicagotribune.com/nation-world/ct-nw-nyt-qassem-soleimani-iran-20200103-6cfuwdo5cfhi7aocmrhn75nbse-story.html |archive-date=3 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, radio host [[Hugh Hewitt]] asked Donald Trump about Soleimani. After initially confusing him with a [[Kurds|Kurdish]] leader, Trump argued that leaders like Soleimani would be dead under his administration.<ref>{{Citation |last=Relman |first=Eliza |title=Trump didn't know who the Iranian leader he just assassinated was four years ago |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://www.businessinsider.nl/trump-didnt-know-who-qassem-soleimani-was-4-years-ago-2020-1?international=true&r=US |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105190115/https://www.businessinsider.nl/trump-didnt-know-who-qassem-soleimani-was-4-years-ago-2020-1?international=true&r=US |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in 2015 that [[Israel]] was \"on the verge\" of assassinating Soleimani on Syrian soil; however, the U.S., during the Obama administration's negotiations for the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action, thwarted the operation by revealing it to the Iranian officials.<ref>{{Citation |title=Report: U.S. Gives Israel Green Light to Assassinate Iranian General Soleimani |date=1 January 2018 |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/u-s-gives-israel-green-light-to-assassinate-iran-s-general-soleimani-1.5630156 |work=[[Haaretz]] |access-date=3 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118102838/https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/u-s-gives-israel-green-light-to-assassinate-iran-s-general-soleimani-1.5630156 |archive-date=18 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 August 2019, [[Israeli Foreign Minister]] [[Israel Katz]] said, \"Israel is acting to strike the head of the Iranian snake and uproot its teeth{{nbsp}}... Iran is the head of the snake and Qassem Soleimani, the commander of the Revolutionary Guards Quds Force, is the snake's teeth.\"<ref>{{Citation |title=After drone strike foiled, top minister threatens Iran commander Soleimani |date=25 August 2019 |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/after-drone-strike-foiled-minister-appears-to-threaten-iran-commander-soleimani/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=3 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826032025/https://www.timesofisrael.com/after-drone-strike-foiled-minister-appears-to-threaten-iran-commander-soleimani/ |archive-date=26 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2019, [[Hossein Taeb]], chief of the [[Intelligence Organization of the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]], told the press that his agency had arrested an unspecified number of people, allegedly foiling a plot by Israeli and Arab agencies to assassinate Soleimani. He said they had planned to \"buy a property adjacent to the grave of Soleimani's father and rig it with explosives to kill the commander\".<ref>{{Citation |title=Iran says it foiled plot to kill Quds chief Soleimani |date=3 October 2019 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-soleimani/iran-says-it-foiled-plot-to-kill-quds-chief-soleimani-idUSKBN1WI161 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004174922/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iran-soleimani/iran-says-it-foiled-plot-to-kill-quds-chief-soleimani-idUSKBN1WI161 |archive-date=4 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He added the way of the assassination would have appeared as part of an internal Iranian power struggle to \"trigger a religious war inside Iran\".<ref>{{Citation |last=Khoury |first=Jack |title=Iran Says Foiled 'Israeli-Arab' Plot to Assassinate Top General Qassem Soleimani |date=3 October 2019 |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/iran-says-foiled-israeli-arab-plot-to-assassinate-top-general-qassem-soleimani-1.7928836 |work=[[Haaretz]] |access-date=4 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205504/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/iran-says-foiled-israeli-arab-plot-to-assassinate-top-general-qassem-soleimani-1.7928836 |archive-date=3 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Yossi Cohen]], chief of the Israeli foreign intelligence agency ([[Mossad]]), said in response, \"Soleimani knows that his assassination is not impossible.\"<ref>{{Citation |title=Mossad chief: Iran's Soleimani 'knows his assassination is not impossible' |date=11 October 2019 |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/mossad-chief-says-irans-soleimani-knows-his-assassination-is-not-impossible/ |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=3 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011070637/https://www.timesofisrael.com/mossad-chief-says-irans-soleimani-knows-his-assassination-is-not-impossible/ |archive-date=11 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 January 2020, ''The New York Times'' author [[Steven Simon]] wrote in a comment: \"What if the former commander of Iran's Revolutionary Guards, Qassim Suleimani, visits Baghdad for a meeting and you know the address? The temptations to use [[hypersonic missile]]s will be many.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/02/opinion/hypersonic-missiles.html |title=Hypersonic Missiles Are a Game Changer |last=Simon |first=Steven |date=2 January 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109192904/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/02/opinion/hypersonic-missiles.html |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Prelude ==\n\n{{See also|2019 K-1 Air Base attack|December 2019 United States airstrikes in Iraq and Syria|2019\u201320 attack on the United States embassy in Baghdad|2019\u201320 Iraqi protests}}\n\nResponse to Iranian major general [[Qasem Soleimani]]'s perceived destructive influence in Iraq and abroad have been a topic of debate amongst U.S. officials for many years. Back in 2006, as the U.S. War in Iraq began to see increasingly sophisticated and lethal roadside bombs,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://admin.govexec.com/media/gbc/docs/pdfs_edit/enclosure_tab_a_document_for_review_(150813_oif_efp_pull_no_summary)_(1).pdf |title= U.S. Casualties associated to EFP events |author1= United States Central Command |date= September 2015 |work= [[United States Central Command]] |accessdate= 18 January 2020 |author1-link= United States Central Command |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113024125/https://admin.govexec.com/media/gbc/docs/pdfs_edit/enclosure_tab_a_document_for_review_%28150813_oif_efp_pull_no_summary%29_%281%29.pdf |archive-date= 13 January 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> such as [[explosively formed penetrators]] (EFPs)\u2014thought to be exclusively due to Iranian influence\u2014<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-sees-new-weapon-in-iraq-iranian-efps/ |title= U.S. Sees New Weapon In Iraq: Iranian EFPs |author1= [[CBS News]]/[[Associated Press]] |date= 11 February 2007 |work= [[CBS News]] |accessdate= 18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211175048/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-sees-new-weapon-in-iraq-iranian-efps/ |archive-date= 11 February 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://publications.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/3667.pdf |title= The U.S. Army in the Iraq War, Volume 1. Invasion\u2014Insurgency\u2014Civil War. 2003\u20132006 |editor1= Colonel Joel D. Rayburn |editor2= Colonel Frank K. Sobchak |6=  |author1= Lieutenant Colonel Jeanne F. Godfroy |8=  |author2= Colonel Matthew D. Morton |10=  |author3= Colonel James S. Powell |12=  |author4= Lieutenant Colonel Matthew M. Zais |date= January 2019 |work= [[Strategic Studies Institute]] and [[United States Army War College|U.S. Army War College Press]] |accessdate= 18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123095420/https://publications.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/3667.pdf |archive-date= 23 November 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> the U.S. military was seeking ways to mitigate the damage. In August 2007, as U.S. military officials attempted to learn more about the leadership of the Iran-backed proxy groups operating in Iraq, they received a message relayed through the Iraqi Minister of State for National Security, that Soleimani wanted them to know that he was \"the sole decision-maker on Iranian activities in Iraq\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://publications.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/3667.pdf |title= The U.S. Army in the Iraq War, Volume 1. Invasion\u2014Insurgency\u2014Civil War. 2003\u20132006 |editor1= Colonel Joel D. Rayburn |editor2= Colonel Frank K. Sobchak |6=  |author1= Lieutenant Colonel Jeanne F. Godfroy |8=  |author2= Colonel Matthew D. Morton |10=  |author3= Colonel James S. Powell |12=  |author4= Lieutenant Colonel Matthew M. Zais |date= January 2019 |work= [[Strategic Studies Institute]] and [[United States Army War College|U.S. Army War College Press]] |accessdate= 18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123095420/https://publications.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/3667.pdf |archive-date= 23 November 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report by NBC News, [[Eric S. Edelman|Eric Edelman]], a career foreign services officer with senior diplomatic posts at the time, U.S. commander [[George W. Casey Jr.|Army Gen. George Casey]] considered designating Soleimani and [[Quds Force]] officers enemy combatants, thus making them subject to military action. However, the idea was ruled out over concerns of opening a \"new front\" in the war. Edelman stated, \"There were a lot of us who thought he should be taken out. But at the end of the day, they decided not to do that,\" due to concern of starting simultaneous conflict with Iran.<ref name=\"NBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/trump-authorized-soleimani-s-killing-7-months-ago-conditions-n1113271 | title= Trump authorized Soleimani's killing 7 months ago, with conditions | author1= Carol E. Lee | author2= Courtney Kube | date= 13 January 2020 | work= [[NBC News]] | accessdate= 18 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113191909/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/trump-authorized-soleimani-s-killing-7-months-ago-conditions-n1113271 | archive-date= 13 January 2020 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, the administration of U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] was the first to designate Soleimani a terrorist on the basis of his involvement with the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps and Quds Force, and the increasing recognition of the role they played in the Iraq conflict.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/hp644.aspx | title= Fact Sheet: Designation of Iranian Entities and Individuals for Proliferation Activities and Support for Terrorism | author1= U.S. Department of the Treasury | date= 25 October 2007 | work= [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]] | accessdate= 18 January 2020 | author1-link= United States Department of the Treasury | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117164517/https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/pages/hp644.aspx | archive-date= 17 January 2020 | url-status= live }}</ref> According to an interview with a [[PolitiFact]] journalist, retired Army Col. Frank Sobchak, said that around the same time U.S. special forces had planned for his capture, but the mission was not approved by senior officials. He said, \"Individuals that we talked to in senior positions of the U.S. government told us that with support for the war at an all time low in 2007, the Bush administration recognized the importance of Soleimani to the war, but was not willing to risk the political capital and repercussions that could occur from expanding the war to that level.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2020/jan/16/donald-trump/fact-checking-trumps-claim-obama-designated-irans-/ | title= Fact-checking Trump's claim that Obama designated Iran's Soleimani a terrorist but did nothing | author1= Tom Kertscher | date= 16 January 2020 | work= [[PolitiFact]] | accessdate= 18 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116220018/https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2020/jan/16/donald-trump/fact-checking-trumps-claim-obama-designated-irans-/ | archive-date= 16 January 2020 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThese activities preceded escalating concern and terror designations of Soleimani by the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]]. The first such designation was made in May, 2011, in response to Soleimani's assistance to the [[General Intelligence Directorate (Syria)|Syrian General Intelligence Directorate]] in the violent suppression of Syrian protestors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1181.aspx | title= Administration Takes Additional Steps to Hold the Government of Syria Accountable for Violent Repression Against the Syrian People | author1= U.S. Department of the Treasury | date= 18 May 2011 | work= [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]] | accessdate= 18 January 2020 | author1-link= United States Department of the Treasury | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517013855/https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/tg1181.aspx | archive-date= 17 May 2019 | url-status= live }}</ref> The second, and more serious designation by the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] came in October, 2011, after a plot was revealed in which four senior Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps-Quds Force (IRGC-QF) officers were planning to assassinate the Saudi Arabian Ambassador while in the United States, under the supervision of Soleimani.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/pages/tg1320.aspx | title= Treasury Sanctions Five Individuals Tied to Iranian Plot to Assassinate the Saudi Arabian Ambassador to the United States | author1= U.S. Department of the Treasury | date= 11 October 2011 | work= [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Department of the Treasury]] | accessdate= 18 January 2020 | author1-link= United States Department of the Treasury | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200118114140/https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/pages/tg1320.aspx | archive-date= 18 January 2020 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nIn early October 2019, according to two Iraqi militia commanders and two security sources who spoke with [[Reuters]] staff, Iranian [[Qasem Soleimani|Major-General Qasem Soleimani]] met in Baghdad to discuss a change in strategy with Iraqi Shiite militia allies.<ref name=\"Reuters staff\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-insight/inside-the-plot-by-irans-soleimani-to-attack-u-s-forces-in-iraq-idUSKBN1Z301Z |title=Inside the plot by Iran's Soleimani to attack U.S. forces in Iraq |last=Reuters staff |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113030452/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-insight/inside-the-plot-by-irans-soleimani-to-attack-u-s-forces-in-iraq-idUSKBN1Z301Z |archive-date=13 January 2020}}</ref> The new focus of strategy was to be an increase in targeted rocket attacks on U.S. forces in Iraq, with the intended effect of provoking an antagonistic U.S. military response that would divert political pressure from Iran. Leading up to the meeting, there had been increasing anti-Iran sentiment amongst the local Iraqi population, culminating in prolonged and vocal anti-Iran protests, even featuring such specific displays of anti-Iran sentiment as demonstrators banging their shoes on raised portraits of [[Ali Khamenei|Ayatollah Ali Khamenei]].<ref name=\"Kasra Aarabi\">{{Cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/11/collapse-iranian-shiism-iraq-lebanon/ |title=Iran's Regional Influence Campaign Is Starting to Flop |last=Kasra Aarabi |date=11 December 2019 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113045749/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/11/collapse-iranian-shiism-iraq-lebanon/ |archive-date=13 January 2020}}</ref> Iran, concerned about losing hard won influence in Iraq, had resorted to increasingly violent means to counter this resentment.<ref name=\"Arwa Ibrahim\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/iraqi-protesters-targeting-iranian-buildings-191128173736467.html |title=Why are Iraqi protesters targeting Iranian buildings? |last=Arwa Ibrahim |date=29 November 2019 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106045101/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/iraqi-protesters-targeting-iranian-buildings-191128173736467.html |archive-date=6 January 2020}}</ref> These means, under direct guidance of Soleimani,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/anti-government-protests-in-iraq-and-lebanon-threatening-iran-s-regional-influence-1.8059140 |title='We in Iran Know How to Deal With Protests,' Soleimani Told Iraqi Officials in Surprise Visit |last=Associated Press |date=31 October 2019 |work=[[Haaretz]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107012906/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/anti-government-protests-in-iraq-and-lebanon-threatening-iran-s-regional-influence-1.8059140 |archive-date=7 January 2020}}</ref> resulted in the deaths of at least 400 protestors, with an estimated 20,000 wounded, but without significant success.<ref name=\"Reuters staff\" /><ref name=\"Kasra Aarabi\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2019/12/killed-central-baghdad-assailants-fire-live-rounds-191206190824237.html |title=Tensions flare as unidentified gunmen kill protesters in Baghdad |last=AL JAZEERA AND NEWS AGENCIES |date=8 December 2019 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228230827/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2019/12/killed-central-baghdad-assailants-fire-live-rounds-191206190824237.html |archive-date=28 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Arwa Ibrahim\" /> The next step in the strategy chosen by Soleimani was to step up attacks on U.S. forces. [[Kata'ib Hezbollah|Kataib Hezbollah]] was picked because, according to Soleimani it \"would be difficult to detect by the Americans\", as well as be able to utilize Iran-provided scout drones for more precision in target selection for the rocket attacks.<ref name=\"Reuters staff\" />\n\nOn 27 December 2019, the K-1 Air Base in [[Kirkuk Governorate|Kirkuk province]], Iraq\u2014one of many Iraqi military bases that host Operation Inherent Resolve coalition personnel\u2014was [[2019 K-1 Air Base attack|attacked]] by more than 30 rockets, killing an [[Iraqi Americans|Iraqi-American]] and Muslim U.S. defense contractor,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/defense-contractor-whose-death-sparked-us-iran-attacks-is-mourned-1.613895 |title=Defense contractor whose death sparked US-Iran attacks is mourned |last=Anita Chabria |date=8 January 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times, [[Stripes.com]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |last2=Leila Miller |last3=Sarah Parvani |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113023931/https://www.stripes.com/news/us/defense-contractor-whose-death-sparked-us-iran-attacks-is-mourned-1.613895 |archive-date=13 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and injuring multiple U.S. and [[Iraqi security forces|Iraqi]] service members.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2019/12/28/several-american-troops-wounded-and-a-us-contractor-killed-in-rocket-attack-on-kirkuk-base/ |title=Several American troops wounded and a US contractor killed in rocket attack on Kirkuk base |last=Snow |first=Shawn |date=27 December 2019 |work=[[MilitaryTimes.com]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112015911/https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2019/12/28/several-american-troops-wounded-and-a-us-contractor-killed-in-rocket-attack-on-kirkuk-base/ |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The U.S. blamed the Iranian-backed Kata'ib Hezbollah militia for the attack.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-usa/trump-aides-call-u-s-strikes-on-iraq-and-syria-successful-warn-of-potential-further-action-idUSKBN1YX0GR |title=Trump aides call U.S. strikes on Iraq and Syria 'successful', warn of potential further action |last=Idrees Ali |date=29 December 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101140018/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-usa/trump-aides-call-u-s-strikes-on-iraq-and-syria-successful-warn-of-potential-further-action-idUSKBN1YX0GR |archive-date=1 January 2020 |last2=Ahmed Rasheed}}</ref> Furthermore, a senior U.S. official, who spoke to reporters on condition of anonymity, said there had been a campaign of 11 attacks on Iraqi bases hosting OIR personnel in the two months before the 27 December incident, many of which the U.S. also attributed to Kata'ib Hezbollah.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/us-airstrikes-iran-tehran-militia-iraq |title=US: strikes on Iran-backed militia a response to 'campaign' of attacks by Tehran |last=Julian Borger |date=30 December 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101232603/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/30/us-airstrikes-iran-tehran-militia-iraq |archive-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/30/state-department-iraq-airstrikes-us-troops-091283 |title=State Department faults Iraq for failing to protect U.S. troops |last=Morgan |first=Wesley |last2=Toosi |first2=Nahal |website=[[Politico]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231173735/https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/30/state-department-iraq-airstrikes-us-troops-091283 |archive-date=31 December 2019 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> On 29 December 2019, retaliatory U.S. airstrikes targeted five Kata'ib Hezbollah weapon storage facilities and [[command and control]] locations in Iraq and Syria.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/29/politics/us-strikes-iran-backed-militia-facilities-in-iraq-syria/index.html |title=US strikes 5 facilities in Iraq and Syria linked to Iranian-backed militia |last=Starr |first=Barbara |date=29 December 2019 |access-date=31 December 2019 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Bohn |first2=Kevin |last3=Levitt |first3=Ross |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230235540/https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/29/politics/us-strikes-iran-backed-militia-facilities-in-iraq-syria/index.html |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-US-Launches\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/29/world/middleeast/us-airstrikes-iran-iraq-syria.html |title=U.S. Launches Airstrikes on Iranian-Backed Forces in Iraq and Syria |date=29 December 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=1 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101014118/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/29/world/middleeast/us-airstrikes-iran-iraq-syria.html |archive-date=1 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> 25 militia members died<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50951742 |title=Kata'ib Hezbollah: Iraq condemns US attacks on Iran-backed militia |date=30 December 2019 |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103073451/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50951742 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> and 55 were wounded.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-insight/inside-the-plot-by-irans-soleimani-to-attack-u-s-forces-in-iraq-idUSKBN1Z301Z|title=Inside the plot by Iran's Soleimani to attack U.S. forces in Iraq|last=Reuters staff|date=3 January 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=4 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106212459/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-insight/inside-the-plot-by-irans-soleimani-to-attack-u-s-forces-in-iraq-idUSKBN1Z301Z|archive-date=6 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2019, after a funeral was held for the Kata'ib Hezbollah militiamen, dozens of Iraqi [[Shia]] militiamen and their supporters marched into the Green Zone and surrounded the U.S. embassy compound.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/31/us-embassy-attack-iraq-091585 |title=Iraqi supporters of Iran-backed militia attack U.S. embassy |date=31 December 2019 |website=[[Politico]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231140016/https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/31/us-embassy-attack-iraq-091585 |archive-date=31 December 2019 |access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref> Dozens of the demonstrators then smashed through a main door of the checkpoint, set fire to the reception area, raised [[Popular Mobilization Units]] militia flags, left [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]] posters, and sprayed anti-American [[graffiti]].<!-- video of the demonstration reportedly showed militiamen trashing the reception area and taking away paperwork. Security staff withdrew to the embassy; there was no immediate comment from [[the Pentagon]] and the [[United States State Department|State Department]]. U.S. ambassador to Iraq [[Matthew H. Tueller|Matt Tueller]] was not at the embassy at the time and was away on previously scheduled \"personal travel\" --><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/your-marine-corps/2019/12/31/100-us-marines-2-apache-helicopters-reinforcing-embassy-in-baghdad-iraq-after-attack/ |title=100 U.S. Marines, two Apache helicopters reinforcing embassy in Baghdad after attack |last=Phillip Athey |date=2 January 2020 |website=[[Marine Corps Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101153056/https://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/your-marine-corps/2019/12/31/100-us-marines-2-apache-helicopters-reinforcing-embassy-in-baghdad-iraq-after-attack/ |archive-date=1 January 2020 |access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/75228a8a607a44863b57021ac33264dc |title=Protesters attack US Embassy in Baghdad after airstrikes |last=Abdul-Zahra |first=Qassim |date=31 December 2019 |website=[[Associated Press]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231100413/https://apnews.com/75228a8a607a44863b57021ac33264dc |archive-date=31 December 2019 |access-date=31 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://time.com/5757228/us-embassy-stormed-iraq-baghdad/ |title=Iraqi Protesters End U.S. Embassy Siege but Tensions Remain High. Here's a Full Timeline |last=Law |first=Tara |date=1 January 2019 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=2 January 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101050621/https://time.com/5757228/us-embassy-stormed-iraq-baghdad/ |archive-date=1 January 2020 |last2=Bates |first2=Josiah}}</ref> U.S. president Donald Trump accused Iran of orchestrating the attack on the embassy and added that they would be held \"fully responsible\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-iraq-security-usa-trump/u-s-has-no-plan-to-evacuate-embassy-in-baghdad-more-forces-being-sent-to-compound-idUKKBN1YZ0T9 |title=U.S. has no plan to evacuate embassy in Baghdad, more forces being sent to compound |last=Ali |first=Idrees |last2=Brunnstrom |first2=David |date=31 December 2019 |website=[[Reuters]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103071115/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-iraq-security-usa-trump/u-s-has-no-plan-to-evacuate-embassy-in-baghdad-more-forces-being-sent-to-compound-idUKKBN1YZ0T9 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> Iran's foreign ministry denied they were behind the protests.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-usa-iran/iran-denies-role-in-u-s-embassy-violence-warns-against-retaliation-idUSKBN1YZ19Y |title=Iran Denies Role in U.S. Embassy Violence, Warns Against Retaliation |date=31 December 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101043402/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-usa-iran/iran-denies-role-in-u-s-embassy-violence-warns-against-retaliation-idUSKBN1YZ19Y |archive-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1212299106321870848 |user=Khamenei_fa |title=\u0645\u06cc\u0628\u06cc\u0646\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0631\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 \u0647\u06cc\u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0636\u062f\u0622\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u06a9\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0686\u0642\u062f\u0631 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u061f \u0628\u0627\u0632 \u0622\u0646 \u062c\u0646\u0627\u0628 \u062a\u0648\u06cc\u06cc\u062a \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u06a9\u0647 \u0645\u0627\u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u0631\u0627 \u0627\u0632 \u0686\u0634\u0645 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0628\u06cc\u0646\u06cc\u0645. \u0634\u0645\u0627 \u063a\u0644\u0637 \u0645\u06cc\u06a9\u0646\u06cc\u062f! \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u06af\u0631\u0628\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0647\u062f\u0628\u0627\u06a9\u0634\u0648\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u0628\u0627\u0631\u0632\u0647 \u06a9\u0646\u062f\u0635\u0631\u06cc\u062d \u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0631\u0627 \u0645\u06cc\u06a9\u0646\u062f.\u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0647 \u0645\u0646\u0627\u0641\u0639 \u0648 \u0639\u0632\u062a \u0645\u0644\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u067e\u0627\u06cc\u0628\u0646\u062f\u06cc\u0645 \u0648\u0647\u0631\u06a9\u0633 \u0622\u0646 \u0631\u0627 \u062a\u0647\u062f\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u0646\u062f \u0628\u062f\u0648\u0646 \u0647\u06cc\u0686 \u0645\u0644\u0627\u062d\u0638\u0647\u200c\u0627\u06cc \u0628\u0627\u0627\u0648 \u0631\u0648\u0628\u0631\u0648 \u0645\u06cc\u0634\u0648\u06cc\u0645 \u0648\u0636\u0631\u0628\u0647 \u0645\u06cc\u0632\u0646\u06cc\u0645 |author=Ali Khamenei |author-link=Ali Khamenei |date=1 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020 |language=fa |trans-title=Do you see the excitement of anti-Americanism throughout Iraq? Again, he has tweeted that we see Maine in the eyes of Iran. You're wrong! Iran will do so clearly if it wants to fight the country. We are committed to the interests and dignity of our nation and everyone who threatens it will face it without any consideration.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1212121026072592384 |user=realDonaldTrump |title=... Iran will be held fully responsible for lives lost, or damage incurred, at any of our facilities. They will pay a very BIG PRICE! This is not a Warning, it is a Threat. Happy New Year! |author=Donald Trump |author-link=Donald Trump |retweet=[[Ali Khamenei]] |date=31 December 2019 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Pentagon evaluation ===\n\n[[The Pentagon]] evaluated Soleimani was the leader of Tehran's attacks on [[List of United States Army installations in Iraq|U.S. bases in Iraq]], including the 2019 K-1 Air Base attack and killing of a U.S. civilian, and the [[2019 Iranian shoot-down of American drone|shooting down of a U.S. aerial vehicle]]. Regarding the decision to kill Soleimani, the U.S. focused on both his past actions and a deterrent to his future action as the Pentagon announced that \"he was actively developing plans to attack [[United States Foreign Service|U.S. diplomats]] and service members in Iraq and throughout the region.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50980704 |title=Why kill Soleimani now and what happens next? |last=Marcus |first=Jonathan |date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106224452/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50980704 |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"defense.gov\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/2049534/statement-by-the-department-of-defense/ |title=Statement by the Department of Defense |date=2 January 2020 |publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103031549/https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/2049534/statement-by-the-department-of-defense/ |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/03/baghdad-airport-iraq-attack-deaths-iran-us-tensions |title=Iran general Qassem Suleimani killed in Baghdad drone strike ordered by Trump |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103013024/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/03/baghdad-airport-iraq-attack-deaths-iran-us-tensions |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51068560 |title=Qasem Soleimani: Iran was targeting four US embassies, says Trump |date=10 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=11 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111041518/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51068560 |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trump briefing ===\n\nAccording to an unnamed senior U.S. official, after the bombing of Kata'ib Hezbollah in late December 2019, a security briefing was convened at President Trump's [[Mar-a-Lago]] estate where he and his advisors, including Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]], Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and chairman of the joint chiefs of staff General [[Mark A. Milley|Mark Milley]] discussed how to respond to Iran's alleged role in sponsoring anti-U.S. attacks in Iraq. Reportedly, the [[targeted killing]] of Iranian general Qasem Soleimani, whom U.S. officials regarded as a facilitator of attacks on U.S. personnel in Iraq, was listed as the \"most extreme option\"<ref name=\"NYTHow\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/04/us/politics/trump-suleimani.html |title=As Tensions With Iran Escalated, Trump Opted for Most Extreme Measure |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106161516/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/04/us/politics/trump-suleimani.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> of many options on a briefing slide,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-01-03/how-trump-made-the-decision-to-kill-suleimani |title=How Trump made the decision to kill Suleimani |date=4 January 2020 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106191215/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-01-03/how-trump-made-the-decision-to-kill-suleimani |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> reflecting an alleged practice among Pentagon officials whereby a very extreme option is presented to presidents so as to make other options appear more palatable.<ref name=WPHow /><ref name=NYTHow /> Trump chose the option to kill Soleimani. The president's order prompted the CIA and other U.S. intelligence agencies that have tracked Soleimani's whereabouts for years to locate him on a flight from [[Damascus]] to Baghdad, reportedly to hold meetings with Iraqi militiamen. The air strike would have been called off if Soleimani had been on his way to meet with Iraqi government officials aligned with the U.S.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\nTrump did not advise the top congressional leaders of the [[Gang of Eight (intelligence)|Gang of Eight]] in advance of the strike. Senator [[Lindsey Graham]] indicated Trump had discussed the matter with him in advance of the strike, as he was visiting the president at his Mar-a-Lago estate.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/us/politics/iran-news.html |title=Congressional Leaders Call for Details After U.S. Airstrike on Suleimani |last=Edmondson |first=Catie |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104200750/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/us/politics/iran-news.html |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/pelosi-demands-briefing-us-iran-strike-graham-trump/story?id=68049245 |title=Pelosi demands briefing on US\u2013Iran strike, Graham says he was informed beforehand |last=News |first=A. B. C. |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105223254/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/pelosi-demands-briefing-us-iran-strike-graham-trump/story?id=68049245 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Trump's motivation for the strike ====\n\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', Trump initially rejected the option to target Soleimani on 28 December 2019, but made the decision after being angered by television news reports of the U.S. embassy in Baghdad under attack by Iranian-backed protesters on 31 December.<ref name=\"NYTHow\" /> By late 2{{nbsp}}January, Trump had finalized his decision of the most extreme option his advisors had provided him, which reportedly \"stunned\" top Pentagon officials. The ''Times'' report cited unnamed U.S. officials as saying the intelligence regarding Soleimani's alleged plot against the U.S. was \"thin\" and that the Ayatollah had not approved any operation for Soleimani to carry out. However, General Milley said the intelligence was \"clear and unambiguous\" with a time frame of \"days, weeks\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/soleimani-approved-attack-iraqi-military-base-killed-american/story?id=68056126 |title=Soleimani approved attack on Iraqi military base that killed American: Top US general |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108105933/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/soleimani-approved-attack-iraqi-military-base-killed-american/story?id=68056126 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo and Vice President [[Mike Pence]] were reportedly the most hawkish voices arguing to retaliate against Iran.<ref name=\"Cooper\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/04/us/politics/trump-suleimani.html |title=As Tensions With Iran Escalated, Trump Opted for Most Extreme Measure |last=Cooper |first=Helene |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Schmitt |first2=Eric |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |last4=Callimachi |first4=Rukmini |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106161516/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/04/us/politics/trump-suleimani.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 }}</ref> Vice President Pence later wrote that Soleimani was plotting \"imminent\" attacks on U.S. persons.<ref name=\"Newsweek\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/mike-pence-9-11-iran-suleimani-katie-waldman-1480398 |title=Mike Pence's press secretary supports vice president's disputed claim that Iran General Soleimani was involved in 9/11 |last=Palmer |first=Ewan |date=4 January 2020 |website=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106205517/https://www.newsweek.com/mike-pence-9-11-iran-suleimani-katie-waldman-1480398 |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> U.S. National Security Advisor [[Robert C. O'Brien (attorney)|Robert O'Brien]] insisted that Soleimani \"was plotting to kill, to attack American facilities, and diplomats, soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines were located at those facilities\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stampede-at-funeral-procession-for-iranian-commander-kills-35-11578390888 |title=Iran Fires Missiles at U.S. Forces in Iraq |last=Lubold |first=Gordon |date=7 January 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |last2=Youssef |first2=Nancy A. |quote=White House national security adviser Robert O'Brien told reporters in Washington on Tuesday that General Soleimani \"was plotting to kill, to attack American facilities, and diplomats, soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines were located at those facilities\". |last3=Coles |first3=Isabel |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108010625/https://www.wsj.com/articles/stampede-at-funeral-procession-for-iranian-commander-kills-35-11578390888 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, according to ''[[The Washington Post]]'' on 4 January 2020, Trump wanted to kill Soleimani{{efn|U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] claimed that Soleimani was responsible of planting thousands of [[Improvised explosive device|roadside bombs]] in Iraq and Afghanistan, by saying: \"He was the king of the roadside bombs, great percentages of people don't have legs right now and arms because of this son of a bitch [Qassem Soleimani]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/14/trump-calls-dead-iranian-gen-qassem-soleimani-a-son-of-a-bitch-at-rally/|title=Trump calls dead Iranian Gen. Qassem Soleimani a 'son of a bitch' at rally|website=New York Post|date=14 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116055809/https://nypost.com/2020/01/14/trump-calls-dead-iranian-gen-qassem-soleimani-a-son-of-a-bitch-at-rally/|archive-date=16 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Moreover, British Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] mentioned that Soleimani supplied \"improvised explosive devices to terrorists, which I'm afraid killed and maimed British troops\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/general-qasem-soleimani-had-blood-of-british-troops-on-his-hands-says-boris-johnson-z2q78pxjb|title=General Qasem Soleimani had blood of British troops on his hands, says Boris Johnson|website=The Times|date=9 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116160541/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/general-qasem-soleimani-had-blood-of-british-troops-on-his-hands-says-boris-johnson-z2q78pxjb|archive-date=16 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}} to avoid the appearance of weakness amid the ongoing Persian Gulf crisis, since his decision to call off an airstrike against Iran in summer 2019 after the downing of a U.S. drone had led to what he perceived as negative media coverage. Lawmakers and aides who had spoken to him told the ''Post'' that the president also had the [[2012 Benghazi attack]] in Libya on his mind.<ref name=\"WPHow\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/how-trump-decided-to-kill-a-top-iranian-general/2020/01/03/77ce3cc4-2e62-11ea-bcd4-24597950008f_story.html |title=How Trump decided to kill a top Iranian general |last=Ryan |first=Missy |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |last3=Lamothe |first3=Dan |last4=Hudson |first4=John |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106175924/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/how-trump-decided-to-kill-a-top-iranian-general/2020/01/03/77ce3cc4-2e62-11ea-bcd4-24597950008f_story.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 }}</ref> Furthermore, Mike Pompeo{{efn|According to [[BBC]], U.S. Congressman [[Mike Pompeo]] applied in 2016 for an Iranian travel visa at the [[Embassy of Pakistan, Washington, D.C.]], to monitor the situation there, but his efforts were in vain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51069090|title=Why Soleimani's death is personal for Pompeo|website=BBC|date=15 January 2020|access-date=16 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116135951/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51069090|archive-date=16 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}} had discussed killing Soleimani with Trump months before the strike, but did not garner support from the president or the defense team then in place.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/killing-of-soleimani-follows-long-push-from-pompeo-for-aggressive-action-against-iran-but-airstrike-brings-serious-risks/2020/01/05/092a8e00-2f7d-11ea-be79-83e793dbcaef_story.html |title=Killing of Soleimani follows long push from Pompeo for aggressive action against Iran, but airstrike brings serious risks |last=Hudson |first=John |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |date=5 January 2020 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last3=Harris |first3=Shane |last4=Lamothe |first4=Dan |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107074251/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/killing-of-soleimani-follows-long-push-from-pompeo-for-aggressive-action-against-iran-but-airstrike-brings-serious-risks/2020/01/05/092a8e00-2f7d-11ea-be79-83e793dbcaef_story.html |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, according to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' on 10 January 2020, Trump reportedly told associates after the strike that he was motivated to strike Soleimani for domestic political gain, particularly to sway [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Senators to support him in his upcoming Senate [[Impeachment of Donald Trump|impeachment]] trial.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-new-national-security-team-made-fast-work-of-iran-strike-11578619195 |title=Trump's New National Security Team Made Fast Work of Iran Strike |last=Strobel |first=Michael C. Bender, Michael R. Gordon, Gordon Lubold and Warren P. |date=10 January 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=10 January 2020 |issn=0099-9660 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110033718/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-new-national-security-team-made-fast-work-of-iran-strike-11578619195 |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn the day of the strike, U.S. secretary of state Mike Pompeo asserted the attack was ordered by Trump to disrupt an \"imminent attack\" by Soleimani operatives, although subsequent reports on that rationale were mixed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-insight/inside-the-plot-by-irans-soleimani-to-attack-u-s-forces-in-iraq-idUSKBN1Z301Z |title=Inside the plot by Iran's Soleimani to attack U.S. forces in Iraq |date=3 January 2019 |access-date=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106212459/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-insight/inside-the-plot-by-irans-soleimani-to-attack-u-s-forces-in-iraq-idUSKBN1Z301Z |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/politics/mike-pompeo-iran-soleimani-strike-cnntv/index.html |title=Pompeo: Strike on Soleimani disrupted an 'imminent attack' |last=Stracqualursi |first=Veronica |date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Hansler |first2=Jennifer |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105013126/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/politics/mike-pompeo-iran-soleimani-strike-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Cooper\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/04/politics/trump-iran-soleimani-strike-concerns/index.html |title=Skepticism mounts over evidence of 'imminent' threat that Trump says justified Soleimani killing |last=Cohen |first=Zachary |date=5 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105045746/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/04/politics/trump-iran-soleimani-strike-concerns/index.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 9{{nbsp}}January, Trump said \"We did it because they were looking to blow up our embassy. We also did it for other reasons that were very obvious. Somebody died, one of our military people died. People were badly wounded just a week before.\"<ref>[https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/09/trump-soleimani-embassy-plot-096717 Trump claims Soleimani was planning to blow up U.S. embassy] ''Politico'', 9{{nbsp}}January 2020</ref> On 10 January, Trump claimed that Soleimani had been planning attacks on four U.S. embassies in the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-tells-laura-ingraham-four-embassies-were-targeted-in-imminent-threat-from-iran |title=Trump tells Fox News' Laura Ingraham 'four embassies' were targeted in imminent threat from Iran |last=Pappas |first=Alex |date=10 January 2020 |website=[[Fox News]] |language=en-US |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111122116/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-tells-laura-ingraham-four-embassies-were-targeted-in-imminent-threat-from-iran |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Afterwards several members of Congress, including [[Mike Lee (American politician)|Mike Lee]] and [[Chris Murphy]], claimed that the Trump administration had not informed them of this in the intelligence briefing on the strike.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/jan/11/trump-iran-fox-news-ingraham-suleimani |title=Donald Trump's Iran claims on Fox News met with skepticism and complaint |last=Pengelly |first=Martin |date=11 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112003332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/jan/11/trump-iran-fox-news-ingraham-suleimani |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Three days after Trump's remarks, Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]] clarified that, although \"there was evidence\" of a plot against the U.S. embassy in Baghdad, the president \"didn't cite intelligence\" about the other three embassies he mentioned, and that the president instead shared his belief that there \"probably could have been\" a plot against those embassies.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/12/us/politics/esper-iran-trump-embassies.html|title=Esper Says He Didn't See Specific Evidence Iran Planned to Attack 4 Embassies|first=Thomas|last=Gibbons-Neff|date=12 January 2020|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115160622/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/12/us/politics/esper-iran-trump-embassies.html|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/FaceTheNation/status/1216359717607481350 |title=NEWS: @EsperDod tells @margbrennan he \"didn't see\" specific evidence showing Iran planned to strike 4 U.S. embassies, despite @realDonaldTrump saying an attack at multiple embassies was \"imminent\". Watch more of Esper's interview on @FacetheNation today.pic.twitter.com/1Nud8waok1 |last=Nation |first=Face The |date=12 January 2020 |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112224639/https://twitter.com/facethenation/status/1216359717607481350 |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/mark-esper-trump-iran-embassies-evidence_n_5e1b2901c5b650c621e02da8 |title=Mark Esper: I 'Didn't See' Specific Evidence Of Iran Threat To 4 U.S. Embassies |last=Miller |first=Hayley |date=12 January 2020 |website=HuffPost |language=en |access-date=13 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113020417/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/mark-esper-trump-iran-embassies-evidence_n_5e1b2901c5b650c621e02da8 |archive-date=13 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January, [[CNN]] reported that President Trump claimed that Soleimani was \"saying bad things about our country\", then he asked \"How much of this shit do we have to listen to?{{nbsp}}... How much are we going to listen to?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/18/politics/trump-soleimani-details-mar-a-lago/index.html|title=Trump recounts minute-by-minute details of Soleimani strike to donors at Mar-a-Lago|website=CNN|date=18 January 2020|access-date=18 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200118090435/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/18/politics/trump-soleimani-details-mar-a-lago/index.html|archive-date=18 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Soleimani's trip to Iraq ===\n\nAdil Abdul-Mahdi, Prime Minister of Iraq, said he was scheduled to meet Soleimani on the day the attack happened, with the purpose of Soleimani's trip being that Soleimani was delivering Iran's response to a previous message from Saudi Arabia which Iraq had relayed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200106-pm-irans-soleimani-was-in-iraq-to-discuss-relations-with-saudi/ |title=PM: Iran's Soleimani was in Iraq to discuss relations with Saudi |date=6 January 2020 |website=The Middle East Monitor |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106141238/https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200106-pm-irans-soleimani-was-in-iraq-to-discuss-relations-with-saudi/ |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Abdul-Mahdi, Trump had called him to request that Abdul-Mahdi mediate the conflict between the U.S. and Iran before the drone strike.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://time.com/5759101/iraqi-parliament-vote-for-us-withdrawal/ |title=Iraqis Push for U.S. Troop Withdrawal in Symbolic Vote |last=Hennigan |first=W. J. |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |last2=Dozier |first2=Kimberly |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106234146/https://time.com/5759101/iraqi-parliament-vote-for-us-withdrawal/ |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/01/iraqis-vote-to-expel-u-s-as-soleimani-fallout-worsens.html |title=Iraqi Lawmakers Vote to Expel U.S. Troops As Fallout From Soleimani Strike Worsens |last=Danner |first=Chas |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106234147/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/01/iraqis-vote-to-expel-u-s-as-soleimani-fallout-worsens.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Attack ==\n\n[[File:MQ-9 Reaper aerial video DOD 107212162-5e1342c0d88af.webm|thumb|An MQ-9 Reaper drone in flight]]\n\nOn 3 January 2020, at 12:32{{nbsp}}a.m. local time, General Soleimani's [[Airbus A320]] [[Cham Wings]] plane arrived at Baghdad International Airport from [[Damascus International Airport]] after being delayed for two hours for unknown reasons.<ref name=\"exclusive_reuters\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-exclusive/exclusive-informants-in-iraq-syria-helped-us-kill-irans-soleimani-sources-idUSKBN1Z829L |title=Exclusive: Informants in Iraq, Syria helped U.S. kill Iran's Soleimani\u2014sources |date=9 January 2020 |website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=10 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109223501/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-soleimani-exclusive/exclusive-informants-in-iraq-syria-helped-us-kill-irans-soleimani-sources-idUSKBN1Z829L |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/tracked-targeted-killed-qassem-soleimanis-final-hours |title=Tracked, targeted, killed: Qassem Soleimani's final hours |date=4 January 2020 |website=Middle East Eye |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111082613/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/tracked-targeted-killed-qassem-soleimanis-final-hours |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|Soleimani used to avoid using his private plane because of increasing concerns regarding his own security, according to an Iraqi security source familiar with his security precautions.<ref name=\"exclusive_reuters\" />}} An [[General Atomics MQ-9 Reaper|MQ-9 Reaper]] drone of the [[U.S. Air Force]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/worlds-most-feared-drone-cias-mq-9-reaper-killed-soleimani |title=World's most feared drone: CIA's MQ-9 Reaper killed Soleimani |last=Read |first=Russ |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[Washington Examiner]] |quote=Iranian General Qassem Soleimani was killed Thursday night in a strike by an MQ-9 Reaper drone. |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107065457/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/worlds-most-feared-drone-cias-mq-9-reaper-killed-soleimani |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|The drone, which was reported to have been launched from Qatar ([[Al Udeid Air Base]]), was controlled remotely by operators at the [[Creech Air Force Base]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1608386/middle-east |title=Reaper drone launched from Qatar fired missile that killed Soleimani |date=5 January 2020 |website=Arab News |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105223101/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1608386/middle-east |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} and other military aircraft loitered above the area{{efn|Investigators in Iraq and Syria have concentrated on how collaborators inside the Damascus and Baghdad airports aided the U.S. military to track and pinpoint Soleimani's position.<ref name=\"exclusive_reuters\" /> In addition, [[NBC News]] reported that [[Israel]] helped in confirming the details provided by the informants.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mideast/airport-informants-overhead-drones-how-u-s-killed-soleimani-n1113726 |title=Airport informants, overhead drones: How the U.S. killed Soleimani |date=10 January 2020 |website=NBC News |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113044145/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/mideast/airport-informants-overhead-drones-how-u-s-killed-soleimani-n1113726 |archive-date=13 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} as Soleimani and other pro-Iranian paramilitary figures, including [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]], a U.S.-designated terrorist,<ref name=\"Lawrence\" /> entered two vehicles and departed the airport towards downtown Baghdad. At 12:47{{nbsp}}a.m., the Reaper drone launched several missiles,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/11/us/politics/iran-trump.html |title=Seven Days in January: How Trump Pushed U.S. and Iran to the Brink of War |last=Baker |first=Peter |date=11 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=13 January 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Bergman |first2=Ronen |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |quote=At 12:47, the first of several missiles smashed into the vehicles, engulfing them in flames and leaving 10 charred bodies inside. |last3=Kirkpatrick |first3=David D. |last4=Barnes |first4=Julian E. |last5=Rubin |first5=Alissa J. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112230801/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/11/us/politics/iran-trump.html |archive-date=12 January 2020 }}</ref>{{efn|The MQ-9 Reaper drone was probably equipped with [[AGM-114 Hellfire]] missiles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/03/a-look-at-the-deadly-capabilities-of-the-mq-9-reaper-drone-that-took-out-gen-qassem-soleimani/ |title=A look at the deadly capabilities of the MQ-9 Reaper drone that took out General Qassem Soleimani |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[The New York Post]] |access-date=10 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110115911/https://nypost.com/2020/01/03/a-look-at-the-deadly-capabilities-of-the-mq-9-reaper-drone-that-took-out-gen-qassem-soleimani/ |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/sebastienroblin/2020/01/04/did-the-pentagon-use-new-joint-air-to-ground-missiles-in-killing-of-general-soleimani/ |title=Did The U.S. Use New Joint Air-To-Ground Missile To Kill Iran's General Soleimani? |date=4 January 2020 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=10 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110055620/https://www.forbes.com/sites/sebastienroblin/2020/01/04/did-the-pentagon-use-new-joint-air-to-ground-missiles-in-killing-of-general-soleimani/ |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} striking the convoy on an access road as it departed the airport,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin Chulov |title='A defining moment in the Middle East': the killing of Qassem Suleimani |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/03/defining-moment-in-middle-east-the-killing-qassem-suleimani |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=3 January 2020 |quote=The US airstrike hit Suleimani's vehicle on an access road at about 2am as he was leaving Baghdad airport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Four Hellfire missiles and a severed hand: The killing of Qassem Soleimani |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/four-hellfire-missiles-and-a-severed-hand-the-killing-of-qassem-soleimani/ |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=The Times of Israel |quote=As the vehicles headed down the airport access road, the drone unleashed four Hellfire missiles}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/e36db7c72c1adba1a6cae75091bc273d |title=Iran vows 'harsh' response to US killing of top general |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103084921/https://apnews.com/e36db7c72c1adba1a6cae75091bc273d |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020| quote=\"The strike, on an access road near Baghdad\u2019s airport, was carried out early Friday\"}}</ref> engulfing the two cars in flames and killing 10 people.<ref>Gal Perl Finkel, [https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/The-killing-of-Soleimani-and-the-Deal-of-the-Century-617741 Potential for strategic turns], [[The Jerusalem Post]], February 16, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"Reuters-Iran\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/02/world/middleeast/qassem-soleimani-iraq-iran-attack.html |title=U.S. Strike in Iraq Kills Qassim Suleimani, Commander of Iranian Forces |last=Crowley |first=Michael |date=2 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103022034/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/02/world/middleeast/qassem-soleimani-iraq-iran-attack.html |archive-date=3 January 2020 |last2=Hassan |first2=Falih |last3=Schmitt |first3=Eric |quote=\"The strike was the second attack at the airport within hours.\"}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.axios.com/qasem-soleimani-killed-iran-baghdad-dc347be1-e847-4c56-92ab-fcc18352d840.html |title=U.S. kills top Iranian commander Qasem Soleimani |last=Lawler |first=Dave |date=2 January 2020 |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs news of the event broke, the U.S. Department of Defense issued a statement which said that the strike was carried out \"at the direction of the president\" and was meant to deter future attacks. Trump asserted that Soleimani had been planning further attacks on American diplomats and military personnel and had approved the attack on the American embassy in Baghdad.<ref name=\"defense.gov\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/03/baghdad-airport-iraq-attack-deaths-iran-us-tensions |title=Iran general Qassem Suleimani killed in Baghdad drone strike ordered by Trump |last=Borger |first=Julian |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103013024/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/03/baghdad-airport-iraq-attack-deaths-iran-us-tensions |archive-date=3 January 2020 |last2=Chulov |first2=Martin}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/03/top-iranian-general-qassim-soleimani-killed-in-us-airstrike-in-baghdad-pentagon.html |title=Top Iranian general killed in US airstrike in Baghdad, Pentagon confirms |date=2 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103032150/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/03/top-iranian-general-qassim-soleimani-killed-in-us-airstrike-in-baghdad-pentagon.html |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Saudi-based ''[[Arab News]]'', the drone that struck Soleimani's convoy had been launched from [[Al Udeid Air Base]] in [[Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1608386/middle-east |title=Reaper drone launched from Qatar fired missile that killed Soleimani |date=5 January 2020 |publisher=[[Arab News]] |url-status=live |access-date=13 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105223101/https://www.arabnews.com/node/1608386/middle-east |archive-date=5 January 2020 }}</ref> A statement by the Air Force of Iran's Islamic Revolution Guards Corps (IRGC) stated that [[Ali Al Salem Air Base]] in Kuwait participated, among other bases in the region, in the operation that was executed near Baghdad airport recently. Kuwait summoned the Iranian ambassador to Kuwait over the statement and expressed Kuwait's resentment and categorical denial at such statement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/24/c_138731803.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124175904/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/24/c_138731803.htm |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Casualties ===\n\n[[File:Abu Mahdi al-Muhandes & Qasem Soleimani01.jpg|thumb|General [[Qasem Soleimani]] (left) and [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]] were among those killed.]]\n\nSoleimani's body was identified using a ring that he wore.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/5597ff0f046a67805cc233d5933a53ed |title=US kills Iran's most powerful general in Baghdad airstrike |last=Karam |first=Zeina |date=2 January 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=2 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103023408/https://apnews.com/5597ff0f046a67805cc233d5933a53ed |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|[[United States special operations forces|U.S. Special Operations forces]] (SOF) were about {{convert|0.5|mi|m}} behind Soleimani's convoy when it was targeted. However, SOF were on the scene within few minutes and performed a [[bomb damage assessment]], where they dragged Soleimani's body out, and took pictures of it along with his belongings, including his damaged cellphone which made further investigations impossible.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/us-special-operations-forces-soleimani-strike-aftermath-photos |title=Photos taken by US Special Operations forces show aftermath of strike that killed Soleimani |date=12 January 2020 |website=Fox News |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112112244/https://www.foxnews.com/world/us-special-operations-forces-soleimani-strike-aftermath-photos |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} As DNA results were still pending regarding the identification of those killed, a senior Pentagon official said there was \"high probability\" that Soleimani would be identified.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/02/793208096/iraqi-tv-says-top-iranian-military-leader-killed-in-rocket-strikes-on-iraqi-airp |title=Pentagon Says Top Iranian Military Leader Killed in Airstrikes On Iraqi Airport |last=Campbell |first=Barbara |date=2 January 2020 |access-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103025649/https://www.npr.org/2020/01/02/793208096/iraqi-tv-says-top-iranian-military-leader-killed-in-rocket-strikes-on-iraqi-airp |archive-date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/iraq-militia-official-killed-us-iran-tensions-1480181 |title=Trump orders U.S. drone strike killing Iranian general who had \"plans to attack\" American diplomats and military |last=Tom O'Connor |date=2 January 2020 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103030530/https://www.newsweek.com/iraq-militia-official-killed-us-iran-tensions-1480181 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |last2=James LaPorta}}</ref> [[Ahmed Al Asadi]], a spokesman for the Popular Mobilization Forces (PMF), confirmed the deaths of Soleimani and Muhandis.<ref name=\"Reuters-Iran\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-soleimani/irans-soleimani-and-iraqs-muhandis-killed-in-air-strike-militia-spokesman-idUSKBN1Z201C |title=Iran's Soleimani and Iraq's Muhandis killed in air strike: militia spokesman |date=2 January 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103022212/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-soleimani/irans-soleimani-and-iraqs-muhandis-killed-in-air-strike-militia-spokesman-idUSKBN1Z201C |archive-date=3 January 2020|quote=\"an air strike on their convoy in Baghdad airport\"}}</ref> According to Ayatollah [[Ali Sistani]]'s office, the casualties included \"several commanders who defeated [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] terrorists\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-reaction-factbox/factbox-reactions-to-the-killing-of-iranian-general-in-a-u-s-air-strike-idUSKBN1Z2070 |title=Factbox: Reactions to the killing of Iranian general in a U.S. air strike\u2014IRAQ'S TOP SHI'ITE CLERIC, AYATOLLAH ALI AL-SISTANI |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103063500/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-reaction-factbox/factbox-reactions-to-the-killing-of-iranian-general-in-a-u-s-air-strike-idUSKBN1Z2070 |archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) said a total of ten people were killed. Along with Soleimani, four other IRGC officers were also killed: Brigadier General Hossein Pourjafari, Colonel Shahroud Mozafarinia, Major Hadi Taremi and Captain Vahid Zamanian.<ref>{{Citation |last=Havasi |first=Amir |title=Iran Threatens Revenge As It Mourns Guards Killed By US |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/iran-threatens-revenge-it-mourns-guards-killed-us-2895702 |work=International Business Times |access-date=3 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103162943/https://www.ibtimes.com/iran-threatens-revenge-it-mourns-guards-killed-us-2895702 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The remaining five casualties were Iraqi members of the PMF: deputy chairman [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]], chief of protocol and public relations Muhammed Reza al-Jaberi,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/us-kills-top-iranian-general-soleimani-in-baghdad-airstrike/a-51873465 |title=US kills top Iranian General Soleimani in Baghdad airstrike |date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103052305/https://www.dw.com/en/us-kills-top-iranian-general-soleimani-in-baghdad-airstrike/a-51873465 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> Mohammad al-Shibani, Hassan Abdul Hadi and Heydar Ali.<ref>{{Citation |last=Sagneli |first=M. |title=Revelan el momento del ataque de drones contra el general Soleimani |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://vanguardia.com.mx/articulo/revelan-el-momento-del-ataque-de-drones-contra-el-general-soleimani-video |work=Vanguardia |access-date=3 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103193250/https://vanguardia.com.mx/articulo/revelan-el-momento-del-ataque-de-drones-contra-el-general-soleimani-video |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' contrasted the attack to [[Operation Vengeance]] in [[World War II]], when American pilots shot down the plane carrying Admiral [[Isoroku Yamamoto]], which the paper said was \"the last time the United States killed a major military leader in a foreign country\".<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\n=== Contemporaneous assassination attempt ===\n\nOn the same day of the Baghdad airport attack, an IRGC financier and key commander, [[Abdul Reza Shahlai]],{{efn|The [[United States Department of State]]'s [[Rewards for Justice Program]] offers up to 15 million USD in rewards for financial background information about the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps and its branches, including information related to Abdul Reza Shahlai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://rewardsforjustice.net/english/irgc.html |title=Act of Terror: Information on Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps |website=Rewards for Justice |access-date=14 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221154803/https://rewardsforjustice.net/english/irgc.html |archive-date=21 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} was unsuccessfully targeted by U.S. drones in Yemen,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/on-the-day-us-forces-killed-soleimani-they-launched-another-secret-operation-targeting-a-senior-iranian-official-in-yemen/2020/01/10/60f86dbc-3245-11ea-898f-eb846b7e9feb_story.html |title=On the day U.S. forces killed Soleimani, they targeted a senior Iranian official in Yemen |date=10 January 2020 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=11 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111032100/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/on-the-day-us-forces-killed-soleimani-they-launched-another-secret-operation-targeting-a-senior-iranian-official-in-yemen/2020/01/10/60f86dbc-3245-11ea-898f-eb846b7e9feb_story.html |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> which killed Mohammad Mirza, a Quds Force operative, instead.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/01/10/us-strike-abdul-reza-shahlai-yemen/ |title=U.S. Strike on Iranian Commander in Yemen the Night of Suleimani's Assassination Killed the Wrong Man |date=10 January 2020 |website=[[The Intercept]] |access-date=11 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111032747/https://theintercept.com/2020/01/10/us-strike-abdul-reza-shahlai-yemen/ |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Shahlai was also responsible for the killing of five American soldiers in [[Karbala]], Iraq on 20 January 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2019/12/05/us-offering-15-million-bounty-for-info-on-iranian-who-planned-2007-karbala-attack-that-killed-5-us-troops/ |title=US offering $15&nbsp;million for info on Iranian planner of 2007 Karbala attack that killed 5 US troops |date=5 December 2019 |website=Military Times |access-date=11 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210052546/https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2019/12/05/us-offering-15-million-bounty-for-info-on-iranian-who-planned-2007-karbala-attack-that-killed-5-us-troops/ |archive-date=10 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nAccording to a Washington Post investigation, the unsuccessful operation might indicate a broader operation than previously explained, raising questions about whether the mission was designed to cripple the leadership of the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps or solely to prevent an imminent attack on Americans as originally stated.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/on-the-day-us-forces-killed-soleimani-they-launched-another-secret-operation-targeting-a-senior-iranian-official-in-yemen/2020/01/10/60f86dbc-3245-11ea-898f-eb846b7e9feb_story.html\n|title=On the day U.S. forces killed Soleimani, they targeted a senior Iranian official in Yemen\n|publisher=Washington Post\n|date=January 10, 2020\n|access-date=January 27, 2020\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111032100/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/on-the-day-us-forces-killed-soleimani-they-launched-another-secret-operation-targeting-a-senior-iranian-official-in-yemen/2020/01/10/60f86dbc-3245-11ea-898f-eb846b7e9feb_story.html\n|archive-date=11 January 2020\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\nSoleimani and al-Muhandis' deaths raised tensions between the U.S. and Iran. According to [[France 24]], the targeted killing of Qasem Soleimani \"caused alarm around the world, amid fears that Iranian retaliation against American interests in the region could spiral into a far larger conflict\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200103-a-more-dangerous-world-usa-killing-soleimani-stokes-fears-regional-conflict-iran-iraq-trump |title='A more dangerous world': US killing of Iran's Soleimani stokes fears of regional conflict |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=5 January 2020 |publisher=France 24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104201957/https://www.france24.com/en/20200103-a-more-dangerous-world-usa-killing-soleimani-stokes-fears-regional-conflict-iran-iraq-trump |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:American Paratroopers deploy to Middle East, January 2020.jpg|thumb|U.S. paratroopers assigned to [[1st Brigade Combat Team, 82nd Airborne Division]] deploy to the Middle East following the Baghdad airstrike, 4{{nbsp}}January 2020]]\n\nShortly after the attack, several planes with U.S. service members took off from bases in the [[eastern United States]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/aircraft-carrying-us-troops-take-off-east-coast-bases-after-drone-strike-kills-top-iranian-general-1480199 |title=Aircraft Carrying US Troops Take Off From East Coast Bases After Drone Strike Kills Top Iranian General |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[Newsweek]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103073243/https://www.newsweek.com/aircraft-carrying-us-troops-take-off-east-coast-bases-after-drone-strike-kills-top-iranian-general-1480199 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> The following day, the U.S. Department of Defense announced the deployment of 3,500 members of the [[82nd Airborne Division]] to the region, one of the largest rapid deployments in decades.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/pentagon-deploy-roughly-3500-troops-middle-east-amid/story?id=68052645 |title=Pentagon to deploy roughly 3,500 more troops to Middle East with others placed on alert status, amid tensions with Iran |last=McLaughlin |first=Elizabeth |access-date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103204346/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/pentagon-deploy-roughly-3500-troops-middle-east-amid/story?id=68052645 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Defense officials said the deployment was not directly related to the airstrike which killed Soleimani, but was instead a \"precautionary action in response to increased threat levels against U.S. personnel and facilities\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/u-s-sending-thousands-more-troops-mideast-after-baghdad-attack-n1110081 |title=U.S. to send 3,000 troops to Middle East after embassy attack, Soleimani killing |last=Kube |first=Courtney |access-date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103175512/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/u-s-sending-thousands-more-troops-mideast-after-baghdad-attack-n1110081 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 5{{nbsp}}January, the UK announced that the [[Royal Navy]] will accompany UK-flagged ships through the [[Strait of Hormuz]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Britains-navy-to-escort-UK-flagged-ships-through-Strait-of-Hormuz-613115 |title=Britain's navy to escort UK-flagged ships through Strait of Hormuz |website=The Jerusalem Post &#124; JPost.com |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105044303/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Britains-navy-to-escort-UK-flagged-ships-through-Strait-of-Hormuz-613115 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Alleged Taji road airstrike ===\n\nThe day after the Baghdad airport attack, Iraqi state news reported that there had been another airstrike against a convoy of medical units of the Iraqi Popular Mobilization Forces near [[Camp Taji]] in [[Taji, Iraq|Taji]], north of Baghdad. An Iraqi Army source told Reuters the attack killed six people and critically wounded three.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-01-03/us-air-strike-targets-iraqi-militia-north-of-baghdad-state-tv |title=U.S. Air Strike Targets Iraqi Militia North of Baghdad: State TV |date=3 January 2019 |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |agency=Reuters |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104172556/https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-01-03/us-air-strike-targets-iraqi-militia-north-of-baghdad-state-tv |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The PMF later said there was no senior commander in the convoy, and the [[Kata'ib al-Imam Ali|Imam Ali Brigades]] denied reports of the death of its leader.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-taji-idUSKBN1Z229P |title=Air strikes targeting Iraqi militia kill six: army source |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103233735/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-taji-idUSKBN1Z229P |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The PMF also denied that any medical convoy was targeted at Taji.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/air-raid-targets-hashd-commander-iraq-state-tv-200103233605393.html |title=Iraq, US-led coalition, deny new air strike near Baghdad |access-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104013003/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/air-raid-targets-hashd-commander-iraq-state-tv-200103233605393.html |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There was no information about who conducted the attack. Spokesman for Operation Inherent Resolve Colonel Myles B. Caggins III said the coalition did not do it, while Iraq's Joint Operations Command denied reports of any such attack, saying it was simply a false rumor that spread quickly due to the prior airport strike.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/middleeast/airstrike-iran-backed-forces-iraq/index.html |title=Coalition denies report that airstrike hit Iran-backed paramilitary forces in Iraq |last=Alkhshali |first=Hamdi |date=4 January 2020 |access-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104022211/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/middleeast/airstrike-iran-backed-forces-iraq/index.html |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Iranian response ===\n{{Further|Funeral of Qasem Soleimani}}\n\n[[File:Iranian Marchers Chant \u2018Death to America\u2019 over US Killing of Gen. Soleimani 139810131620232219282811.webm|thumb|left|start=00:08|Demonstrations in Iran over the death of Soleimani, 3{{nbsp}}January 2020. Video by [[Tasnim News]].]]\n\nA spokesman for the Iranian government said the country's top security body would hold an extraordinary meeting shortly to discuss the \"criminal act of attack\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50979463 |title=Top Iranian general killed by US in Iraq |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103025417/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50979463 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> Iran's Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]] warned that \"retaliation is waiting\".<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/soleimani-killing-iran-abandons-nuclear-deal-limits-200105185905943.html US\u2013Iran tensions after Soleimani killing: All the latest updates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109084742/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/soleimani-killing-iran-abandons-nuclear-deal-limits-200105185905943.html |date=9 January 2020 }} Al Jazeera, 5 January 2020</ref> On 4{{nbsp}}January, the [[U.S. Department of Homeland Security]] said there was \"no specific, credible\" threat to the U.S. mainland but warned about Iranian capabilities.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/476797-dhs-says-no-credible-threat-to-us-warns-of-groups-capability DHS says no 'credible' threat to US, warns of groups' capability] BY RACHEL FRAZIN, The Hill, 4 January 2020</ref> Trump warned Tehran that any retaliation would result in the U.S. targeting 52 Iranian significant sites, including [[List of World Heritage Sites in Iran|cultural sites]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/suleimani-killing-donald-trump-defends-threat-to-hit-cultural-sites-in-iran Suleimani killing: Donald Trump defends threat to target cultural sites in Iran] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109040729/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/06/suleimani-killing-donald-trump-defends-threat-to-hit-cultural-sites-in-iran |date=9 January 2020 }} ''The Guardian'', 6 January 2020</ref> The 52 sites were reported to represent the 52 American hostages held during the [[Iran hostage crisis]].<ref>[https://www.euronews.com/2020/01/05/iran-warns-trump-that-targeting-cultural-heritage-is-a-war-crime Trump defends his threat to target Iranian cultural sites] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105214726/https://www.euronews.com/2020/01/05/iran-warns-trump-that-targeting-cultural-heritage-is-a-war-crime |date=5 January 2020 }} Euronews, 5 January 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/05/world/middleeast/trump-cultural-sites.html Defenders of History Take Aim at Trump's Threat to Strike Iran's Cultural Sites] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106124203/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/05/world/middleeast/trump-cultural-sites.html |date=6 January 2020 }} ''The New York Times'', 5 January 2020</ref> [[Hossein Dehghan]], the main military adviser of Iran, and Iranian Foreign Minister [[Javad Zarif]] asserted that attacks on Iranian cultural sites would be grave breaches of international law. U.S. secretary of state Mike Pompeo avoided a direct answer when asked about cultural targets, saying that Washington will do the things that are right and the things that are consistent with U.S. law.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/05/world/trump-iran-cultural-sites-war-crime/index.html |title=Trump's threatened attack on Iranian cultural sites could be a war crime if carried out |last=Levenson |first=Eric |date=5 January 2020 |access-date=11 January 2020 |website=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111105850/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/05/world/trump-iran-cultural-sites-war-crime/index.html |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> U.S. secretary of defense Mark Esper later asserted that cultural sites would not be targeted because \"That's the laws of armed conflict.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/esper-iran-cultural-sites-trump/index.html |title=Esper contradicts Trump on targeting Iranian cultural sites: We 'follow the laws of armed conflict' |last=Starr |first=Barbara |date=6 January 2020 |access-date=8 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Browne |first2=Ryan |last3=LeBlanc |first3=Paul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108020743/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/esper-iran-cultural-sites-trump/index.html |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 January 2020, the [[Islamic Consultative Assembly]] of Iran chanted \"America, the [[Great Satan|greatest Satan]]\", during its session.<ref>''[[Tagesschau (German TV series)|Tagesschau]]'' edition on 5 January 2020 at 20:00</ref> That day, Iran announced that it would suspend all its commitments under the 2015 nuclear deal<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/iran-pulling-out-nuclear-deal-following-u-s-strike-killed-n1110636 |title=Iran pulling out of nuclear deal commitment after U.S. strike that killed Soleimani |last=Burman |first=Max |date=5 January 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105185759/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/iran-pulling-out-nuclear-deal-following-u-s-strike-killed-n1110636 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> except that it would continue to cooperate with the United Nations' nuclear watchdog, the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]]. The statement added, \"If the sanctions are lifted{{nbsp}}... the Islamic Republic is ready to return to its obligations.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51001167 |title=Iran rolls back nuclear deal commitments |date=5 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105195039/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51001167 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |access-date=5 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/body-of-commander-slain-by-us-strike-arrives-in-iran-to-crowds-of-mourners/2020/01/05/4ca3281a-2f17-11ea-bffe-020c88b3f120_story.html |title=Iran announces it is suspending its commitments to the 2015 nuclear deal |last=Cunningham |first=Erin |date=5 January 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105120822/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/body-of-commander-slain-by-us-strike-arrives-in-iran-to-crowds-of-mourners/2020/01/05/4ca3281a-2f17-11ea-bffe-020c88b3f120_story.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aerial Footage of Funeral Procession for General Soleiman in Tehran 13981016000475.webm|thumb|right|upright=0.9|start=00:05|Aerial footage of Soleimani's funeral procession in [[Tehran]]. Video from [[FARS News Agency]].]]\n\nThe remains of Soleimani and the Iranian figures killed in the strike arrived in Iran on 5{{nbsp}}January, where they became part of mourning processions in several cities, first in [[Ahvaz]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hJSmVcpMEq8 |title=Thousands flock to mourn Qasem Soleimani in Iran |date=5 January 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref> and later in [[Mashhad]], where one million people attended the mourning. It was initially reported that Iran canceled the mourning procession planned in Tehran because the city would not be able to handle the number of attendees expected after the turnout in Mashhad;<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/iran-cancels-soleimani-ceremony-in-tehran-after-massive-turnout-in-second-city/ |title=Iran cancels Soleimani ceremony in Tehran after massive turnout in second city |date=5 January 2019 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105221132/https://www.timesofisrael.com/iran-cancels-soleimani-ceremony-in-tehran-after-massive-turnout-in-second-city/ |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6AjxVj2Yhgc |title=LIVE: Farewell ceremony for Iran's Quds Force General Soleimani in the Iranian city of Mashhad |date=5 January 2019 |work=Ruptly |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107012222/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6AjxVj2Yhgc |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> however, the Tehran service was held, at which Ayatollah Ali Khamenei publicly wept while leading prayers for the funeral. Iranian state media said the crowd of mourners numbered in the \"millions\", reportedly the biggest since the 1989 funeral of the founder of the Islamic Republic, Ayatollah [[Ruhollah Khomeini]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-khamenei/iran-leader-khamenei-leads-prayers-at-soleimani-funeral-idUSKBN1Z50IU |title=Iran leader Khamenei leads prayers at Soleimani funeral |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106094523/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-khamenei/iran-leader-khamenei-leads-prayers-at-soleimani-funeral-idUSKBN1Z50IU |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KzldnUAHIXg |title=LIVE: Funeral for Iran's Quds Force General Soleimani in the Iranian city of Tehran |date=6 January 2019 |work=Ruptly |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107003758/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KzldnUAHIXg |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iranian authorities plan to take Soleimani's body to [[Qom]] on 6{{nbsp}}January for public mourning processions,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Y7_ULmhhO0 |title=LIVE: Funeral procession for Quds Force General Soleimani in Iranian city of Qom |date=6 January 2019 |work=Ruptly |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107001726/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Y7_ULmhhO0 |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> then onto his hometown of [[Kerman]] for final burial on 7{{nbsp}}January.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/soleimanis-body-arrives-iran-trump-issues-threats-68074424 |title=Soleimani's body arrives in Iran as Trump issues new threats |date=5 January 2019 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105060736/https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/soleimanis-body-arrives-iran-trump-issues-threats-68074424 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C0i163LOKpg |title=LIVE: Burial of Iran's Quds Force General Soleimani in his home town Kerman |date=7 January 2019 |work=Ruptly}}</ref> Before the national procession was completed, multiple infrastructure works, such as the [[Ahvaz International Airport|international airport at Ahvaz]] and [[Qasem Soleimani Expressway|an expressway in Tehran]], had already been renamed after him.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://parstoday.com/en/news/iran-i115113-iran_renames_airport_route_after_lieutenant_general_soleimani |title=Iran renames airport, route after Lieutenant General Soleimani |date=6 January 2020 |work=Pars Today |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107231911/https://parstoday.com/en/news/iran-i115113-iran_renames_airport_route_after_lieutenant_general_soleimani |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/05/world/middleeast/iran-suleimani-funeral.html |title=Mourners Throng Iran's Streets for Suleimani Funeral Marches |last=Fassihi |first=Farnaz |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106154013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/05/world/middleeast/iran-suleimani-funeral.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The funeral was boycotted by critics of the current government by using the hashtag #IraniansDetestSoleimani for the IRGC's war crimes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fox10phoenix.com/news/coup-revolution-and-war-events-that-propped-up-soleimani-reveal-why-iran-is-split-on-his-death |title=Coup, revolution and war: Events that propped up Soleimani reveal why Iran is split on his death |date=6 January 2020 |website=FOX TV Digital Team |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107055633/https://www.fox10phoenix.com/news/coup-revolution-and-war-events-that-propped-up-soleimani-reveal-why-iran-is-split-on-his-death |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ir.voanews.com/a/soleimani-socialmedia-reaction/5234218.html |title=\u062a\u0648\u0641\u0627\u0646 \u062a\u0648\u0626\u06cc\u062a\u0631\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u067e\u0627\u0633\u062e \u0628\u0647 \u062a\u0628\u0644\u06cc\u063a\u0627\u062a \u0631\u0633\u0627\u0646\u0647\u200c\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u062d\u06a9\u0648\u0645\u062a\u06cc: \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u06af\u0648\u06cc\u0646\u062f \u0627\u0632 \u0633\u0644\u06cc\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc \"\u0645\u062a\u0646\u0641\u0631\" \u0647\u0633\u062a\u0646\u062f |website=\u0635\u062f\u0627\u06cc \u0622\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107082713/https://ir.voanews.com/a/soleimani-socialmedia-reaction/5234218.html |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The hashtag was amplified by \"inauthentic\" accounts almost immediately after creation.<ref name=\"buzz_TheI\">{{Cite web |title=The Iranian Woman In The #IraniansDetestSoleimani Viral Video Was Also A Lobbyist For A Militia In Libya |author= |work=BuzzFeed News |date= |access-date=20 February 2020 |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ryanhatesthis/the-iranian-woman-in-the-iraniansdetestsoleimani-viral|quote=In addition to its organic engagement, Kasraie\u2019s YouTube video was boosted by being tagged #IraniansDetestSoleimani, a hashtag that was amplified by inauthentic Twitter accounts several minutes after the video was posted.}}</ref><ref name=\"medi_Inau\">{{Cite web |title=Inauthentic Twitter Accounts Continue Pushing For War With Iran |last=Golberg |first=Geoff |work=Medium |date= |access-date=20 February 2020 |url=https://medium.com/@geoffgolberg/inauthentic-twitter-accounts-continue-pushing-for-war-with-iran-d828c9870797|quote=Translated: nearly 1/5th of the accounts (998) identified in our post from October have recently tweeted, retweeted or were mentioned in tweets where #IraniansDetestSoleimani appears}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2020, at least 56 people were killed and 213 injured in a stampede during Soleimani's burial at Kerman. As a result, the burial was postponed to a later time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51015795 |title=Stampede kills 50 at Soleimani's burial in Iran |date=7 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107104128/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51015795 |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2020/01/07/iran-qasem-soleimani-funeral-procession-deaths/2830680001/ |title=Stampede at Iranian commander Qasem Soleimani's funeral kills at least 56 |last=Hjelmgaard |first=Kim |website=[[USA Today]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112021637/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2020/01/07/iran-qasem-soleimani-funeral-procession-deaths/2830680001/ |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a speech<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.memri.org/tv/iranian-president-rouhani-nuclear-industries-prosper-coming-years-we-do-not-have-proxies-region |title=Rouhanis speech from Januar 8th 2020 translated by MEMRI |access-date=18 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111152956/https://www.memri.org/tv/iranian-president-rouhani-nuclear-industries-prosper-coming-years-we-do-not-have-proxies-region |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> broadcast on 8 January on Iranian television [[Islamic Republic of Iran News Network|IRINN&nbsp;TV]] and translated by the [[Middle East Media Research Institute]] into English, Iranian President Rouhani stated that Iran will no longer stick to the 2015 nuclear agreement restrictions on uranium enrichment: \"Iran's nuclear industry will prosper\" he said. Secondly, Rouhani mentioned in his speech that \"They cut off the hand of our dear Soleimani\" and as revenge they, the Iranians, would cut off the legs of the Americans and toss them out of neighboring countries.\n\n==== Iranian missile strikes on Iraqi\u2014U.S. bases ====\n\n{{Main|Operation Martyr Soleimani}}\n\nShortly after the confirmation of Soleimani's death, U.S. spy agencies reportedly detected that Iran's [[ballistic missile]] regiments were at a heightened readiness but it was unclear at the time if they were defensive, cautionary measures or an indication of a future attack on U.S. forces.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/readied-iran-ballistic-missiles-were-detected-prompting-trump-tweet-2020-1 |title=US spies detected Iranian ballistic missiles at a heightened state of readiness following the assassination of Qassem Soleimani |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106043551/https://www.businessinsider.com/readied-iran-ballistic-missiles-were-detected-prompting-trump-tweet-2020-1 |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, Iranian forces launched ballistic missiles at the [[Al Asad Airbase]] and an airbase near [[Erbil]], both in Iraq, where American personnel were located.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/07/politics/rockets-us-airbase-iraq/index.html |title=Trump says 'Iran appears to be standing down' following its retaliatory attacks |last=Gaouette |first=Nicole |date=7 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Alkhshali |first2=Hamdi |last3=Browne |first3=Ryan |last4=Starr |first4=Barbara |last5=Qiblawi |first5=Tamara |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107234444/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/07/politics/rockets-us-airbase-iraq/index.html |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/iran-launches-missiles-us-air-bases-iraq-us/story?id=68130625 |title=Iran launches missiles at US military facilities in Iraq: US official |last=Martinez |first=Luis |date=7 January 2020 |work=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |access-date=7 January 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107233750/https://abcnews.go.com/International/iran-launches-missiles-us-air-bases-iraq-us/story?id=68130625 |archive-date=7 January 2020 }}</ref> The Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps declared that the strikes were part of their retaliation for the killing of Soleimani.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Multiple-rockets-hit-Taji-base-in-Iraq-hosting-American-troops-613476 |title=IRGC: Missile attack on US bases in Iraq is revenge for Soleimani killing |last=Joffre |first=Tzvi |date=8 January 2020 |work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107220502/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Multiple-rockets-hit-Taji-base-in-Iraq-hosting-American-troops-613476 |archive-date=7 January 2020 }}</ref> No Iraqi or American casualties were reported.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-government-idUSKBN1Z71FX |title=Iraqi PM received word from Iran about missile attack |date=8 January 2020 |website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109182804/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-government-idUSKBN1Z71FX |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Iranian Students News Agency]] (ISNA), the country's state-run news outlet, Iran fired \"tens of ground-to-ground missiles\" at the base and claimed responsibility for the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/iran-launches-missiles-us-air-bases-iraq-us/story?id=68130625 |title=Iran launches missiles into US air bases in Iraq: US official |publisher=[[ABC News]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107233750/https://abcnews.go.com/International/iran-launches-missiles-us-air-bases-iraq-us/story?id=68130625 |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The attacks unfolded in two waves, each about an hour apart.<ref name=\"Miles\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/missile-attacks-target-us-forces-in-iraq-senior-military-source-says-iran-suspected |title=Iran launches 15 ballistic missiles into Iraq targeting US, coalition forces, officials say |last=Miles |first=Frank |date=7 January 2020 |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108000654/https://www.foxnews.com/world/missile-attacks-target-us-forces-in-iraq-senior-military-source-says-iran-suspected |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Pentagon said these bases were on high alert after signs of the Iranian government were planning attacks on U.S. forces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/2052103/dod-statement-on-iranian-ballistic-missile-attacks-in-iraq/ |title=DOD Statement on Iranian Ballistic Missile Attacks in Iraq |website=United States Department of Defense |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108003059/https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/2052103/dod-statement-on-iranian-ballistic-missile-attacks-in-iraq/ |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Although the Pentagon disputes the number launched, it has confirmed that both the Ayn al-Asad and the Erbil airbases were hit by Iranian missiles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/07/trump-iran-suleimani-threats-retaliation |title=Iran crisis: missiles launched against US airbases in Iraq |last=Borger |first=Julian |date=8 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |last2=Wintour |first2=Patrick |location=London |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107223313/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/07/trump-iran-suleimani-threats-retaliation |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/07/politics/rockets-us-airbase-iraq/index.html |title=Trump says 'Iran appears to be standing down' following its retaliatory attacks |last=Gaouette |first=Nicole |date=8 January 2020 |access-date=8 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Alkhshali |first2=Hamdi |last3=Browne |first3=Ryan |last4=Starr |first4=Barbara |last5=Qiblawi |first5=Tamara |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107234444/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/07/politics/rockets-us-airbase-iraq/index.html |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A military spokesman for [[United States Central Command|U.S. Central Command]] said a total of 15 missiles were fired. Ten hit the Ayn al-Asad airbase, one hit the Erbil base, and four missiles failed.<ref name=\"Miles\" /> Other sources confimed that two ballistic missiles targeted Erbil: one hit [[Erbil International Airport]] and did not explode, the other landed about {{convert|20|mi|km}} west of Erbil.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/us-iran-soleimani-tensions-intl-01-07-20/h_c633b7ccb8e78db079f9e3079f989870 |title=Two ballistic missiles hit Erbil, sources say |last=Alkhshali |first=Hamdi |date=7 January 2020 |access-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200108032722/https://www.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/us-iran-soleimani-tensions-intl-01-07-20/h_c633b7ccb8e78db079f9e3079f989870 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> On 8{{nbsp}}January [[Saudi Arabia]]'s Deputy Defense Minister [[Khalid bin Salman bin Abdulaziz Al Saud|Prince Khalid bin Salman]] said the Kingdom would stand with Iraq and do everything in its power to spare it from the \"danger of war and conflict between external parties\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nonperele.com/saudi-arabia-will-do-everything-to-spare-iraq-the-danger-of-war-vice-minister/|title=Saudi Arabia will do everything to spare Iraq the danger of war: vice minister|accessdate=8 January 2020|website=Non Perele|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113041950/https://nonperele.com/saudi-arabia-will-do-everything-to-spare-iraq-the-danger-of-war-vice-minister/|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Brent crude oil futures prices, August 2019 through January 2020 (49467835818).png|thumb|upright=1.4|Impact of the attack, and Iranian retaliation, on [[Brent crude]] oil prices (bottom right, green)]]\nGlobal oil prices rose moderately in reaction to Soleimani's death to heights not seen for a whole three months,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/716aaeb8-3023-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |title=ACTUAL ARTICLE TITLE BELONGS HERE |website=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106171141/https://www.ft.com/content/716aaeb8-3023-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> before falling back.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/54ff3dfc-311d-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |title=ACTUAL ARTICLE TITLE BELONGS HERE |website=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108162854/https://www.ft.com/content/54ff3dfc-311d-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/oil-traders-lose-faith-in-geopolitical-rallies-11578402000 |title=Oil Traders Lose Faith in Geopolitical Rallies |last=Toy |first=Sarah |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url-access=subscription |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107170809/https://www.wsj.com/articles/oil-traders-lose-faith-in-geopolitical-rallies-11578402000 |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following Iran's zero-fatality missile attack, prices were lower than before the airstrike that killed al-Muhandis.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/9fb38360-3228-11ea-a329-0bcf87a328f2 |title=ACTUAL ARTICLE TITLE BELONGS HERE |website=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109144846/https://www.ft.com/content/9fb38360-3228-11ea-a329-0bcf87a328f2 |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Impact on Iranian protests ====\n\n{{Main|2019\u201320 Iranian protests#January 2020}}\n\nOn 11 January 2020, after Iranian authorities acknowledged that Iranian military forces had shot down [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]], thousands of people [[2019\u201320 Iranian protests#January 2020|protested in Iran]],<ref name=\"ThomReut_protests_leaders2quit\" /> continuing the [[2018\u20132019 Iranian general strikes and protests|Iranian protests ongoing since December 2017]].<ref name=\"BBC_June_risingprices_demo\" /><ref name=\"AlArabiya_4killed_July2018_Death2Khamenei\" /><ref name=\"BBC_2018nov_2nd_teachers_strike\" /><ref name=\"RadioZamaneh_2019March_railway_workers\" /> The protestors called for the Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]] to resign, chanted \"Death to the liars\" and called \"for the IRGC to leave the country\".<ref name=\"AJE_demand_Khameini_quit\" />\n\n=== Iraqi response ===\n\nThe [[Embassy of the United States, Baghdad|U.S. embassy in Baghdad]] urged Americans to leave Iraq immediately \"via airline while possible, and failing that, to other countries via land\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.trust.org/item/20200103080348-ku86v/ |title=U.S. embassy urges citizens to depart Iraq immediately\u2014statement |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103084136/http://news.trust.org/item/20200103080348-ku86v/ |archive-date=3 January 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> The next day, Britain warned its nationals to avoid all travel to Iraq outside the [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdistan]] region, and to avoid all but essential travel to Iran.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Britain-warns-nationals-against-travel-to-Iraq-and-Iran-613064 |title=Britain warns nationals against travel to Iraq and Iran |website=The Jerusalem Post &#124; JPost.com |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104190915/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Britain-warns-nationals-against-travel-to-Iraq-and-Iran-613064 |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Australia]] issued a similar warning advising its nationals to \"leave Iraq as soon as possible\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.smartraveller.gov.au/destinations/middle-east/iraq |title=Iraq Travel Advice & Safety &#124; Smartraveller |website=smartraveller.gov.au |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230093850/https://www.smartraveller.gov.au/destinations/middle-east/iraq |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 4 January, the funeral procession for Soleimani, al-Muhandis, and the Iraqi and Iranian militants was held in Baghdad and attended by thousands of mourners who chanted \"death to America, death to Israel\". Iraqi Prime Minister Adil Abdul-Mahdi was also present.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/iraq-capital-funeral-top-iranian-general-4953429-Jan2020/ |title=Iraq's prime minister joins mourners in Baghdad for funeral of top Iranian general killed by US |website=[[TheJournal.ie|The Journal]] |location=Dublin |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105133137/https://www.thejournal.ie/iraq-capital-funeral-top-iranian-general-4953429-Jan2020/ |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The cortege began around [[Al-Kadhimiya Mosque]], a Shiite holy site in Baghdad, before heading to the Green Zone government and diplomatic compound where a state funeral was held. From Baghdad, the procession moved to the Shia holy city of [[Karbala]] and on to [[Najaf]], where al-Muhandis and the other Iraqis were buried, while the coffins of Soleimani and the Iranian nationals were sent to Iran.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/04/huge-crowds-expected-in-baghdad-for-funeral-of-iranian-general-killed-by-us |title=Qassem Suleimani: 'Death to America' chants at Baghdad funeral procession |last=Safi |first=Ghaith Abdul-Ahad Michael |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |last2=Graham-Harrison |first2=Emma |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106154919/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/04/huge-crowds-expected-in-baghdad-for-funeral-of-iranian-general-killed-by-us |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://time.com/5758868/iraq-mourn-soleimani/ Thousands in Iraq March in Funeral Procession for Iranian General Killed by U.S.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104202413/https://time.com/5758868/iraq-mourn-soleimani/ |date=4 January 2020 }} ''Time'', 4 January 2020</ref> Following the mourning procession in Baghdad,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50991810 |title=Qasem Soleimani: Thousands mourn assassinated Iranian general |last=Doucet |first=Lyse |date=4 January 2020 |access-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108032059/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50991810 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> unknown people fired short-range rockets towards the U.S. embassy and at the U.S. [[Balad Air Base]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/rockets-target-baghdad-green-zone-base-housing-troops-200104175916421.html |title=Rockets target Baghdad's Green Zone, base housing US troops |date=4 January 2020 |access-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104184139/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/rockets-target-baghdad-green-zone-base-housing-troops-200104175916421.html |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The U.S. Central Command, which oversees operations in the Middle East, said no Americans were harmed by the sporadic rocket attacks on 4{{nbsp}}January.<ref name=\"Cooper\" />\n\nOn 6{{nbsp}}January, [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] evacuated all its American oil workers from [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] as a \"precautionary measure\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/business/chevron-workers-iraq/index.html |title=Chevron pulls oil workers from Iraq |last=Egan |first=Matt |date=6 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Ziady |first2=Hanna |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106204548/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/business/chevron-workers-iraq/index.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Status of U.S. troops in Iraq ====\n\n[[Al-Manar]] reported that \"in an extraordinary session on Sunday, 170 Iraqi lawmakers signed a draft law requiring the government to request the withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq. Only 150 votes are needed that the draft resolution be approved.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://english.almanar.com.lb/905643 |title=170 Iraqi MPs Sign Draft Law to Expel U.S. Troops from Iraq\u2014Al-Manar TV Lebanon |website=english.almanar.com.lb |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105201008/http://english.almanar.com.lb/905643 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There are 329 lawmakers in total. [[Rudaw Media Network]] (Kurdish) described the 170 Iraqi lawmakers that signed the law as [[Shiite]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/iraq/05012020 |title=Shiite MPs draft legislation seeking to expel US troops from Iraq |website=rudaw.net |access-date=5 January 2020}}</ref> and that \"Iraqi parliament's resolution to expel foreign troops has no legal consequences.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rudaw.net/english/analysis/05012020 |title=Iraqi parliament's resolution to expel foreign troops has no legal consequences |website=rudaw.net |access-date=5 January 2020}}</ref> [[Al Jazeera]] reported the resolution read \"The government commits to revoke its request for assistance from the international coalition fighting Islamic State due to the end of [[International military intervention against ISIL|military operations]] in Iraq and the achievement of victory\" and \"The Iraqi government must work to end the presence of any foreign troops on Iraqi soil and prohibit them from using its land, airspace or water for any reason.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/iraqi-parliament-calls-expulsion-foreign-troops-200105150709628.html |title=Iraqi parliament calls for expulsion of foreign troops |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105155550/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/iraqi-parliament-calls-expulsion-foreign-troops-200105150709628.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The resolution was approved in the Iraqi parliament.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.axios.com/iraq-parliament-us-troops-iran-soleimani-39f46292-b6b5-4070-bacd-92cfae1f586c.html |title=Iraqi parliament calls on government to expel U.S. troops |access-date=5 January 2020 |website=Axios |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105185317/https://www.axios.com/iraq-parliament-us-troops-iran-soleimani-39f46292-b6b5-4070-bacd-92cfae1f586c.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In response to the vote, Trump threatened Iraq with sanctions that would \"make Iranian sanctions look somewhat tame\" and demanded reimbursement for American investments on military facilities in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/01/06/us-president-trump-threatens-iraq-with-crippling-sanctions |title=Trump threatens Iraq with crippling sanctions |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Euronews]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106094714/https://www.euronews.com/2020/01/06/us-president-trump-threatens-iraq-with-crippling-sanctions |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 2020, the Pentagon released a letter from Marine Brigadier General [[William H. Seely III|William Seely]] to Abdul Amir, the Iraqi deputy director of Combined Joint Operations Baghdad, informing him that \"as requested by the Iraqi Parliament and the Prime Minister, [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|CJTF\u2013OIR]] will be repositioning forces over the course of the coming days and weeks to prepare for onward movement.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/pentagon-initially-told-capitol-hill-iraq-withdrawal-letter-was-fake-report-says |title=Pentagon Initially Told Capitol Hill Iraq Withdrawal Letter Was Fake, Report Says |last=Ross |first=Jamie |date=7 January 2020 |website=[[The Daily Beast]]}}</ref> Shortly afterward, [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[Mark Milley]] said, \"That letter is a draft. It was a mistake, it was unsigned, it should not have been released{{nbsp}}... [it was] poorly worded, implies withdrawal, that is not what's happening.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/us-troops-iraq/index.html |title=Top general says letter suggesting US would withdraw troops from Iraq was a 'mistake' |last=Cohen |first=Zachary |date=6 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Starr |first2=Barbara |last3=Browne |first3=Ryan |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106223301/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/us-troops-iraq/index.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA couple of days later, [[United States Department of State]] warned Iraq to lose access to the [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]] accounts,{{efn|In 2015, the U.S. [[Federal Reserve]] and [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] halted Iraq's access to its funds at the New York Fed accounts for several weeks, fearing that they would be eventually taken by Iranian banks as well as ISIS.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-cut-cash-to-iraq-on-iran-isis-fears-1446526799 |title=U.S. Cut Cash to Iraq on Iran, ISIS Fears |last=Glazer |first=Emily |date=3 November 2015 |last2=Malas |first2=Nour |last3=Hilsenrath |first3=Jon |url-access=subscription |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112060325/https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-cut-cash-to-iraq-on-iran-isis-fears-1446526799 |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Iraq's oil revenues deposited at the Fed were valued at $3{{nbsp}}billion every month at the end of 2018, according to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref name=\"wsj\" /> Meanwhile, Iraqi officials declared that around $35{{nbsp}}billion of the country's oil revenues are held at the U.S. Federal Reserve, which are equal to 90% of the national budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/iraq-warns-collapse-trump-blocks-oil-cash-035946583.html|title=Iraq warns of 'collapse' if Trump blocks oil cash|website=Yahoo!|date=13 January 2020|access-date=19 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113130756/https://news.yahoo.com/iraq-warns-collapse-trump-blocks-oil-cash-035946583.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}} in a phone call if U.S. troops were asked to leave, according to Iraqi officials.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-iraq-it-risks-losing-access-to-key-bank-account-if-troops-told-to-leave-11578759629 |title=U.S. Warns Iraq It Risks Losing Access to Key Bank Account if Troops Told to Leave |date=11 January 2020 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112012312/https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-iraq-it-risks-losing-access-to-key-bank-account-if-troops-told-to-leave-11578759629 |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{efn|In the meantime, U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] mentioned that Iraq should pay back for the facilities built there, if the U.S. military leaves, as their money held in the U.S., otherwise the troops would stay in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/trump-tells-ingraham-iraq-should-pay-u-s-back-otherwise-well-stay-there |title=Trump tells Ingraham Iraq should pay US back if troops leave country |date=11 January 2020 |website=Fox News |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112183301/https://www.foxnews.com/media/trump-tells-ingraham-iraq-should-pay-u-s-back-otherwise-well-stay-there |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Moreover, the Trump administration drafted sanctions against Iraq whether they expel U.S. troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/trump-administration-preparing-economic-sanctions-against-iraq-military-withdrawal-iran-2020-1-1028801079|title=The Trump administration has started preparing economic sanctions against Iraq|website=Markets Insider|date=7 January 2020|access-date=19 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108160131/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/trump-administration-preparing-economic-sanctions-against-iraq-military-withdrawal-iran-2020-1-1028801079|archive-date=8 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nIn mid February, the Iraqi government confirmed to [[NATO]], that they could restart its training missions, which have been paused since the attack. Troops from [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|CJTF\u2013OIR]] are expected to be moved and work under the NATO banner instead.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cook|first=Lorne|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/iraq-green-lights-resumption-nato-training-effort-68959861|title=Iraq green-lights resumption of NATO training effort|date=13 February 2020|work=ABC News|access-date=13 February 2020|agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Emmott|first=Robin|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-nato-idUSKBN2062LD|title=NATO to expand Iraq training mission in response to Trump|date=12 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=13 February 2020|editor-last=Heinrich|editor-first=Mark}}</ref>\n\n==== Impact on Iraqi protests ====\n\n{{Main|Iraqi protests (2019\u2013present)#January}}\n\nThe [[Iraqi protests (2019\u2013present)|sustained massive street protests in Iraq]] that led to Abdul-Mahdi's resignation as prime minister (and temporary caretaker role) restarted in the days after the assassination of Soleimani and al-Muhandis, with a shift in the focus of protests from mostly anti-Iran to criticism of both the U.S. and Iran.<ref name=\"RFarda_Jan2020_iraqprotests\" /><ref name=\"lObs_2020Jan_noUS_noIran\" /><ref name=\"MEE_iraq_protests_20200110\" /> The \"Made in Iraq\" street and online protests strengthened in Baghdad following the assassination.<ref name=\"AlMon_made_in_Iraq\" /> Major protests took place on 5{{nbsp}}January 2020 in many cities,<ref name=\"RFarda_Jan2020_iraqprotests\" /><ref name=\"lObs_2020Jan_noUS_noIran\" /> \"Made in Iraq\" protests on 7{{nbsp}}January,<ref name=\"AlMon_made_in_Iraq\" /> and two thousand protested in [[Basra]] and [[Nassiriyah]] on 10 January, with one of the slogans being \"Neither America nor Iran, our revolution is a young revolution.\"<ref name=\"MEE_iraq_protests_20200110\" />\n\nOn 24 January, several hundred thousand Iraqis protested against U.S. military presence in Iraq and called for them to leave the country after Shia cleric [[Muqtada al-Sadr]] called for a \"Million Man March.\" Iraqi President [[Barham Salih]] tweeted, \"Iraqis insist on a state with complete sovereignty that will not be breached.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/24/middleeast/iraq-protests-us-troops-intl/index.html |title=Hundreds of thousands protest US troop presence in Iraq |work=[[CNN]] |date=24 January 2020 |access-date=24 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124143827/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/24/middleeast/iraq-protests-us-troops-intl/index.html |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Legality ==\nThe airstrike's legal justification became a subject of debate.<ref name=\"Khalel\" /><ref name=\"Kennedy\">{{Citation |last=Kennedy |first=Merrit |title=Was It Legal for the U.S. To Kill A Top Iranian Military Leader? |date=4 January 2020 |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/04/793412105/was-it-legal-for-the-u-s-to-kill-a-top-iranian-military-leader |publisher=[[NPR]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |last2=Northam |first2=Jackie |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104173803/https://www.npr.org/2020/01/04/793412105/was-it-legal-for-the-u-s-to-kill-a-top-iranian-military-leader |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Swart |first=Mia |title='To stop a war': Did Soleimani killing violate international law? |date=5 January 2020 |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/stop-war-soleimani-killing-violate-international-law-200105050718644.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105190319/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/stop-war-soleimani-killing-violate-international-law-200105050718644.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Dilanian\" />\n\n=== Alleged violation of international law ===\n\nThe [[Charter of the United Nations]] generally prohibits the [[Use of force by states|use of force]] against other states, if a country does not consent to it on its territory.<ref name=\"JapanTimes\">{{Citation |title=A question of laws: Was U.S. killing of Iran's Soleimani self-defense or assassination? |date=4 January 2020 |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/04/world/question-laws-u-s-killing-irans-soleimani-self-defense-assassination/ |work=[[Japan Times]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104154124/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2020/01/04/world/question-laws-u-s-killing-irans-soleimani-self-defense-assassination/ |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Government of Iraq]] did not grant permission to the U.S. to target a military commander from another country on its soil.<ref name=\"Dilanian\">{{Citation |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |title=Was it legal for Donald Trump to order the killing of a top Iranian general? |date=4 January 2020 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/was-it-legal-donald-trump-order-killing-top-iranian-general-n1109961 |work=[[NBC]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108130759/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/was-it-legal-donald-trump-order-killing-top-iranian-general-n1109961 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"JapanTimes\" /> Some legal experts believe a lack of consent from Iraq makes it difficult for the U.S. to justify the attack.<ref name=\"JapanTimes\" />\n\n[[Agn\u00e8s Callamard]], the [[United Nations special rapporteur]] on extrajudicial, summary or arbitrary executions, maintained that the airstrike \"most likely violate[d] [[international law]] incl[uding] [[human rights law]]\", adding that killing of other individuals alongside Soleimani was \"absolutely unlawful\".<ref name=\"Khalel\">{{Citation |last=Khalel |first=Sheren |title=Was it legal?: What US and international law say about Trump's strike on Soleimani |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/was-it-legal-what-us-and-international-law-says-about-trumps-strike-soleimani |work=[[Middle East Eye]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |last2=Farooq |first2=Umar A |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104194557/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/was-it-legal-what-us-and-international-law-says-about-trumps-strike-soleimani |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/baghdad-airport-strike-live-intl-hnk/h_f4d89b41ef9e19a716edc8047bf923df |title=Soleimani's killing \"most likely unlawful\", UN rights expert says |last=Dean |first=Sarah |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=5 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Siad |first2=Arnaud |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104145421/https://edition.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/baghdad-airport-strike-live-intl-hnk/h_f4d89b41ef9e19a716edc8047bf923df |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDefence Secretary [[Ben Wallace (politician)|Ben Wallace]] said \"the intelligence information I have seen, under the right to defend yourself against an imminent threat, that would have been met.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/ben-wallace-interview-we-cant-rely-on-us-pmwcgv398 |title=Ben Wallace interview: We can't rely on US |last=Tim Shipman |date=12 January 2020 |work=[[The Times]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |quote=The intelligence information I have seen, under the right to defend yourself against an imminent threat, that would have been met. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112051115/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/ben-wallace-interview-we-cant-rely-on-us-pmwcgv398 |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A spokesman for [[Boris Johnson]], Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, said, \"States have a right to take action such as this in self-defence.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/iran-war-trump-boris-johnson-cultural-sites-soleimani-iraq-a9272076.html |title=Boris Johnson warns Trump after threat to bomb Iran's 52 cultural sites |date=6 January 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106140248/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/iran-war-trump-boris-johnson-cultural-sites-soleimani-iraq-a9272076.html |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson later said \"...{{nbsp}}the strict issue of legality is not for the UK to determine since it was not our operation\", in response to [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]] [[Jeremy Corbyn]] who called it an \"illegal act\" and asked for the government to condemn it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/iran-crisis-boris-johnson-trump-soleimani-corbyn-commons-quds-a9275336.html |title=Iran crisis: Boris Johnson gives strongest backing yet to Trump over US killing of Soleimani |date=8 January 2020 |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=10 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108211508/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/iran-crisis-boris-johnson-trump-soleimani-corbyn-commons-quds-a9275336.html |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Mary Ellen O'Connell]] argued that the \"premeditated killing\" of Soleimani was against the [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague]] (1907) and [[Protocol I|Geneva]] (1949) conventions, and thus unlawful.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/01/03/us/ap-us-iran-was-it-an-assassination-.html |title=Was the Drone Attack on Iranian General an Assassination? |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> [[Robert M. Chesney]] maintained that the attack could be justifiable if it was \"[[self-defense]]\"; [[Oona A. Hathaway]] said the available facts did not support that.<ref name=\"JapanTimes\" />\n\n[[NBC News]] correspondents reported that according to five current and former Trump administration officials, Trump had authorized the killing Soleimani back in June, 2019, on the condition that \"Iran's aggression resulted in the death of an American.\" According to the correspondents, given the overall timeline of events, this report may call into question for some the Trump administration's citied reason of \"imminent threats\" as a cause of the killing.<ref name=\"NBC News\" />\n\nIran said it will pursue a [[war-crimes]] case against US president Donald Trump at the [[International Criminal Court]] in the Hague.<ref name=\"Hague\">{{cite news |last1=Prothero |first1=Mitch |title=Iran has a 'shockingly strong' war-crimes case against Trump over Soleimani's killing \u2014 and it could win |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-iran-qassem-soleimani-war-crimes-lawsuit-could-win-2020-1 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Business Insider |date=2020-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200120105416/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-iran-qassem-soleimani-war-crimes-lawsuit-could-win-2020-1 |archive-date=20 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== In terms of agreement with Iraq ===\n\n{{See also|U.S.\u2013Iraq Status of Forces Agreement}}\n\nPMF is legally incorporated into the Iraqi security forces by a series of laws enacted by the parliament and Prime Ministerial orders, therefore, technically, the U.S. killed a senior Iraqi official ([[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]]) and other military personnel of Iraq.<ref>{{Citation |last=Smith |first=Crispin |title=United States Killed Iraqi Military Official and Iraqi Military Personnel in the Two Recent Attacks |date=5 January 2020 |url=https://www.justsecurity.org/67917/united-states-killed-iraqi-military-official-and-iraqi-military-personnel-in-the-two-recent-attacks/ |work=[[Just Security]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105173446/https://www.justsecurity.org/67917/united-states-killed-iraqi-military-official-and-iraqi-military-personnel-in-the-two-recent-attacks/ |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Rubin |first=Alissa J. |title=Cries of 'Revenge Is Coming' at Funerals for Slain Commanders in Iraq |date=4 January 2020 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/04/world/middleeast/iraq-funeral-general-soleimani-al-muhandis.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |quote=Tens of thousands mourned the killing of a major Iraqi official and a top Iranian general by a U.S. drone strike{{nbsp}}... The militias have since been brought under the umbrella of the Iraqi security forces, and Mr. al-Muhandis was their deputy head. |access-date=5 January 2020 |last2=Hubbard |first2=Ben |last3=Hassan |first3=Falih |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105001150/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/04/world/middleeast/iraq-funeral-general-soleimani-al-muhandis.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA mutual agreement signed in 2008 prohibits the U.S. from launching attacks on other countries from Iraqi territory.<ref name=\"JapanTimes\" /> Iraqi Prime Minister [[Adil Abdul-Mahdi]] said the attack was a \"breach of the conditions for the presence of U.S. forces in Iraq\".<ref>{{Citation |last=Hassan |first=Falih |title=A Shocked Iraq Reconsiders Its Relationship With the U.S. |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/world/middleeast/us-iraq.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |last2=Arango |first2=Tim |last3=Rubin |first3=Alissa J. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105014410/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/world/middleeast/us-iraq.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He also said \"The assassination of an Iraqi military commander who holds an official position is considered [[War of aggression|aggression]] on Iraq{{nbsp}}... and the liquidation of leading Iraqi figures or those from a brotherly country on Iraqi soil is a massive breach of sovereignty.\"<ref name=\"Kennedy\" /> He and [[List of Speakers of the Council of Representatives of Iraq|Speaker of the Council of Representatives]] [[Mohamed al-Halbousi]] released separate written statements, both calling the attack a breach of Iraq's [[sovereignty]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Ibrahim |first=Arwa |title=Iraq braces for 'difficult days' after Soleimani's killing |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/iraq-braces-difficult-days-soleimani-killing-200103122412024.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105075149/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/iraq-braces-difficult-days-soleimani-killing-200103122412024.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Rasheed |first=Ahmed |title=Iraqi parliament speaker condemns U.S. air strike: statement |date=3 January 2020 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-speaker/iraqi-parliament-speaker-condemns-us-air-strike-statement-idUSKBN1Z21BD |work=[[Reuters]] |editor-last=El Dahan |editor-first=Maha |access-date=5 January 2020 |last2=Aboulenein |first2=Ahmed}}</ref>\nAccording to the office of the Iraqi caretaker prime minister, the U.S. secretary of state has subsequently been requested to send a delegation to Iraq tasked with formulating the mechanism for the withdrawal of U.S troops from Iraq.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/182bae76452d7565b0a3d840ff0369cb |title=Iraqi PM tells US to decide mechanism for troop withdrawal |date=10 January 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=10 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110154708/https://apnews.com/182bae76452d7565b0a3d840ff0369cb |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Domestic laws of the United States ===\n\nSome U.S. individuals noted that since the airstrike was orchestrated without the specific authorization of [[United States Congress|Congress]], there were a number of legal questions.<ref name=\"Dilanian\" /> The case was compared by AP reporter [[John Daniszewski]] to the drone killing of U.S. citizen [[Anwar al-Awlaki]] during the Obama administration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stripes.com/why-soleimani-s-killing-is-different-from-other-targeted-attacks-by-us-1.613506 |title=Why Soleimani's killing is different from other targeted attacks by US |website=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/us/articles/2020-01-03/was-the-drone-attack-on-iranian-general-an-assassination |title=Was the Drone Attack on Iranian General an Assassination? |date=4 January 2020 |website=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106101643/https://www.usnews.com/news/us/articles/2020-01-03/was-the-drone-attack-on-iranian-general-an-assassination |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deseret.com/indepth/2020/1/3/21048613/qassem-soleimani-trump-iran-drone-strike |title=News analysis: Did the drone strike on an Iranian general set a dangerous global precedent? |last=Billingsley |first=Dodge |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[Deseret News]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104141434/https://www.deseret.com/indepth/2020/1/3/21048613/qassem-soleimani-trump-iran-drone-strike |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/why-soleimanis-killing-is-different-from-other-targeted-attacks-by-u-s/ |title=Why Soleimani's killing is different from other targeted attacks by U.S. |last=Siobh\u00e1n O'Grady |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105082332/https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/why-soleimanis-killing-is-different-from-other-targeted-attacks-by-u-s/ |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some analysts maintained that Trump had the authority to order the strike under [[Article Two of the United States Constitution]], while the ambiguity of the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists]] (AUMF) law may help Trump justify it.<ref name=\"Khalel\" />\n\n[[Executive Order 11905]], signed in 1976, to prevent [[assassination attempts on Fidel Castro]], states that \"no person employed by or acting on behalf of the United States Government shall engage in, or conspire to engage in, assassination.\" The definition of assassination under the law\u2014or whether it could be applied to this case\u2014is not clear.<ref name=\"NYT-US-Launches\" />\n\nOn 14 February 2020, in a legally required unclassified memorandum<ref>https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/_cache/files/4/3/4362ca46-3a7d-43e8-a3ec-be0245705722/6E1A0F30F9204E380A7AD0C84EC572EC.doc148.pdf</ref> to Congress, the Trump administration said it was authorised under both the Constitution and the 2002 Authorisation of Use of Military Force Against Iraq.<ref name=\"Shifting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/timeline-trump-shifting-justifications-soliemani-killing-200217222143105.html|title=Timeline of Trump's shifting justifications for Soleimani killing|publisher =AlJazeera|date=February 18, 2020|access-date = February 18, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==== Congressional resolution to limit Trump's war powers ====\n\nSome members of Congress, which generally was not consulted or briefed before the Soleimani strike, sought to restrict the president's ability to conduct future military operations against Iran without congressional consent. On 6{{nbsp}}January 2020, House Speaker Pelosi announced plans to hold a vote within the week on limiting President Trump's [[war powers]] concerning Iran.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/06/house-to-vote-on-limiting-trumps-military-powers-regarding-iran.html |title=House to vote on limiting Trump's military powers regarding Iran, Pelosi says |last=Ellyatt |first=Holly |date=6 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109032546/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/06/house-to-vote-on-limiting-trumps-military-powers-regarding-iran.html |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 8{{nbsp}}January 2020, Pelosi announced that a vote will be held by the entire House on 9{{nbsp}}January to limit President Trump's war powers concerning any future escalation of conflict with Iran.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/pelosi-announces-thursday-vote-war-powers-resolution-n1112651 |title=Pelosi announces vote to limit Trump's war powers on Iran |publisher=[[NBC News]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109074316/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/pelosi-announces-thursday-vote-war-powers-resolution-n1112651 |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/08/politics/house-democrats-finalizing-details-iran-war-powers-resolution/index.html |title=House slates Iran War Powers resolution vote for Thursday |last=Byrd |first=Haley |date=8 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Cohen |first2=Zachary |last3=Lybrand |first3=Holmes |last4=Foran |first4=Clare |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108232117/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/08/politics/house-democrats-finalizing-details-iran-war-powers-resolution/index.html |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/01/08/iran-pelosi-house-vote-limit-trump-war-powers/2847709001/ |title=Pelosi sets vote on measure to limit Trump's war powers, citing 'urgent' concerns on Iran strategy |last=Wu |first=Deirdre Shesgreen and Nicholas |website=[[USA Today]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108230027/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/01/08/iran-pelosi-house-vote-limit-trump-war-powers/2847709001/ |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]] cleared the way for a full House vote by approving parameters which set up a two-hour debate on 9{{nbsp}}January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/01/09/white-house-works-crush-debate-over-legality-iran-strike-democrats-move-ahead-war |title=As White House Works to Crush Debate Over Legality of Iran Strike, Democrats Move Ahead With War Powers Vote |website=Common Dreams |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114022118/https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/01/09/white-house-works-crush-debate-over-legality-iran-strike-democrats-move-ahead-war |archive-date=14 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The House vote is considered significant, as the [[Constitution of the United States|U.S. Constitution]] provides that while the president may use the military to defend the country, any [[Declaration of war by the United States|declaration of war]] must be approved by Congress (note that Congress has never declared war on anyone [[Declaration of war by the United States#Formal|since World War II]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/house-vote-limiting-trump-actions-iran-200109144821939.html |title=US House to vote on limiting Trump's actions against Iran |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109193405/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/house-vote-limiting-trump-actions-iran-200109144821939.html |archive-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Trump criticized the effort, arguing that congressional approval should not be needed to militarily engage Iran \"because you have to be able to make split-second decisions sometimes\".<ref name=\"WPR\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-congress-idUSKBN1Z82CB |title=U.S. House passes resolution to limit Trump's ability to wage war on Iran |date=10 January 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=10 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110014604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-congress-idUSKBN1Z82CB |archive-date=10 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\n\n{{Main|Reactions to the 2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike}}\n\nIranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei vowed to take \"harsh revenge\" against the U.S.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2020/01/03/615238/Leader-Soleimani-revenge-US |title=Iran Leader vows 'harsh revenge' following assassination of Gen. Soleimani |date=3 January 2020 |publisher=[[Press TV]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103090246/https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2020/01/03/615238/Leader-Soleimani-revenge-US |archive-date=3 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whio.com/news/world/iraq-least-katyusha-rockets-fired-baghdad-airport/Q6YOHuM4TeDt92KglzQ8iL/ |title=AP: US kills Iran's most powerful general in Baghdad airstrike |date=3 January 2020 |website=whio.com |url-status=live |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104023851/https://www.whio.com/news/world/iraq-least-katyusha-rockets-fired-baghdad-airport/Q6YOHuM4TeDt92KglzQ8iL/ |archive-date=4 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/iran-slams-us-strike-on-top-iranian-general-qasem-soleimani-2020-1 |title=Iran's supreme leader warns a 'harsh retaliation is waiting' for the US, after an American airstrike killed top Iranian general Qassem Soleimani |last=Pickrell |first=Ryan |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104023905/https://www.businessinsider.com/iran-slams-us-strike-on-top-iranian-general-qasem-soleimani-2020-1 |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and declared three [[National day of mourning|days of mourning]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/article/Iraq-At-least-3-Katyusha-rockets-fired-at-14945882.php |title=US kills Iran's most powerful general in Baghdad airstrike |last=Abdul Qassim-Zahra |date=2 January 2020 |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103053917/https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/article/Iraq-At-least-3-Katyusha-rockets-fired-at-14945882.php |archive-date=3 January 2020 |agency=Associated Press |last2=Zeina Karam}}</ref> President [[Hassan Rouhani]] also said Iran \"will take revenge\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/amp/news/articles/2020-01-03/top-iranian-commander-is-killed-in-u-s-airstrike-in-baghdad |title=Top Iranian Commander Killed in U.S. Airstrike on Trump Orders |date=3 January 2020 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103071642/https://www.bloomberg.com/amp/news/articles/2020-01-03/top-iranian-commander-is-killed-in-u-s-airstrike-in-baghdad |archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> Foreign Minister [[Mohammad Javad Zarif]] called the attack \"an extremely dangerous and foolish escalation\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-reaction-factbox/reactions-to-the-killing-of-iranian-general-in-a-u-s-air-strike-idUSKBN1Z2070 |title=Reactions to the killing of Iranian general in a U.S. air strike |date=2 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103052944/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-reaction-factbox/reactions-to-the-killing-of-iranian-general-in-a-u-s-air-strike-idUSKBN1Z2070 |archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> Iran sent a letter to the United Nations, calling it \"[s]tate terrorism\" and said it violated principles of international law.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-iran-un/iran-tells-un-it-reserves-right-to-self-defense-over-soleimani-killing-idUSKBN1Z22A3 |title=Iran tells U.N. it reserves right to self-defense over Soleimani killing |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126212105/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-iran-un/iran-tells-un-it-reserves-right-to-self-defense-over-soleimani-killing-idUSKBN1Z22A3 |archive-date=26 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 7{{nbsp}}January, [[Islamic Consultative Assembly|Iran's parliament]] approved a \u20ac200&nbsp;million increase in the Quds Force's budget, to be used in two months.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d74a76c6-308e-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |title=Iran considers options for retribution over Soleimani killing |date=7 January 2020 |work=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108063206/https://www.ft.com/content/d74a76c6-308e-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Reuters reported that some Iranians including Soleimani supporters fear that a war could break out at a time of economic hardship and widespread corruption. Some older Iranians recalled memories of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-mood/sorrow-mixed-with-fear-as-iran-mourns-soleimanis-death-idUSKBN1Z30FD |title=Sorrow mixed with fear as Iran mourns Soleimani's death |last=Hafezi |first=Parisa |date=4 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104194321/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-mood/sorrow-mixed-with-fear-as-iran-mourns-soleimanis-death-idUSKBN1Z30FD |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn Iraq, outgoing Prime Minister [[Adel Abdul Mahdi]] condemned the attack, calling it an assassination and stating that the strike was an act of aggression and a breach of Iraqi sovereignty which would lead to war in Iraq. He said the strike violated the [[U.S.\u2013Iraq Status of Forces Agreement|agreement on the presence of U.S. forces in Iraq]] and that safeguards for Iraq's security and sovereignty should be met with legislation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/iraqi-pm-condemns-us-killing-of-irans-soleimani |title=Iraqi PM condemns US killing of Iran's Soleimani |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[The Straits Times]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103083209/https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/iraqi-pm-condemns-us-killing-of-irans-soleimani |archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> The speaker of Iraq's parliament Mohammed al Halbousi vowed to \"put an end to U.S. presence\" in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/iraqi-parliament-vows-to-put-an-end-to-us-presence-in-country |title=Iraqi parliament vows to 'put an end to US presence' in country |last=Neale |first=Spencer |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104035947/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/iraqi-parliament-vows-to-put-an-end-to-us-presence-in-country |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Iraqi parliament voted to ask U.S. to withdraw their forces from Iraq. [[Muqtada al-Sadr]], leader of the [[Sadrist Movement]] and the [[Peace Companies|Saraya al-Salam]] militia, ordered his followers to \"prepare to defend Iraq\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-sadr/iraqs-sadr-mourns-soleimani-says-followers-ready-to-defend-iraq-statement-idUSKBN1Z20H0 |title=Iraq's Sadr mourns Soleimani, says followers ready to defend Iraq: statement |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103084835/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-blast-sadr/iraqs-sadr-mourns-soleimani-says-followers-ready-to-defend-iraq-statement-idUSKBN1Z20H0 |archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:President Trump Delivers a Statement on Iran January 3 2020.webm|thumb|U.S. president Donald Trump delivers prepared remarks on the airstrikes, [[Mar-a-Lago]], 3{{nbsp}}January 2020]]\n\nShortly before the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] announced the strike, President Trump posted a [[Flag of the United States|U.S. flag]] on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-tweets-photo-of-american-flag-us-claims-iran-airstrike-2020-1 |title=Trump tweeted a photo of the American flag minutes before the Pentagon claimed the US killed Iran's top military general in an airstrike |last=Perper |first=Rosie |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103052533/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-tweets-photo-of-american-flag-us-claims-iran-airstrike-2020-1 |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/realdonaldtrump/status/1212924762827046918 |title=pic.twitter.com/VXeKiVzpTf |last=Trump |first=Donald J. |date=2 January 2020 |website=@realdonaldtrump |access-date=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104065711/https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1212924762827046918 |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next morning held a public statement saying he had authorized the strike because Soleimani was plotting \"imminent and sinister attacks\" on Americans. He added, \"We took action last night to stop a war. We did not take action to start a war.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/politics/donald-trump-iran-statement/index.html |title=Trump on strike that killed Soleimani: 'We did not take action to start a war' |last=Liptak |first=Kevin |date=3 January 2019 |access-date=4 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Vazquez |first2=Maegan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104022224/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/politics/donald-trump-iran-statement/index.html |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He also said he did not seek a regime change in Iran.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/03/trump-to-make-a-statement-following-fatal-strike-on-iran-general.html |title=Trump says US does not seek war or regime change in Iran, but is still ready to act if 'necessary' |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=6 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105203101/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/03/trump-to-make-a-statement-following-fatal-strike-on-iran-general.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 4{{nbsp}}January, Trump tweeted that 52 Iranian targets (representing the 52 American hostages in the [[Iran hostage crisis|1979\u201381 Iran hostage crisis]]) had been selected if Iran \"strikes any Americans, or American assets\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/04/politics/trump-warning-iran-52-assets/index.html |title=Trump warns Iran if it hits any Americans or American assets 'we have targeted 52 Iranian sites |last=Diamond |first=Jeremy |date=4 January 2020 |access-date=11 January 2020 |last2=Kelly |first2=Caroline |last3=Clary |first3=Greg |website=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111100135/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/04/politics/trump-warning-iran-52-assets/index.html |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/world/iran-trump-warns-iran-we-have-targeted-52-iranian-sites Trump warns Iran: US has targeted '52 Iranian sites' and will 'hit very fast and very hard' if needed] Fox News Channel, 4 January 2020.</ref> Iranian President Rouhani responded to Trump's warning: \"Those who refer to the number 52 should also remember the number 290\", referring to the 1988 shooting down of an [[Iran Air Flight 655]], by a U.S. warship in which 290 were killed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/middle-east-north-africa/476970-rouhani-points-to-downing-of-iranian-airliner |title=Rouhani points to US downing of Iranian airliner in response to Trump threat |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107065435/https://thehill.com/policy/international/middle-east-north-africa/476970-rouhani-points-to-downing-of-iranian-airliner |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Among those targets were [[United States threat for destruction of Iranian cultural sites|Iranian \"cultural sites\"]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/trumps-threats-draw-irans-cultural-sites-into-tensions/2020/01/05/417241ba-2fc6-11ea-971b-43bec3ff9860_story.html |title=Trump's threats draw Iran's cultural sites into tensions |agency=AP |first=Aya |last=Batrawy |website=[[The Washington Post]] |quote=If culturally prominent sites were targeted, the Trump administration might argue they were being used to covertly stockpile weapons that could target U.S. interests and personnel in the region. |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105185213/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/trumps-threats-draw-irans-cultural-sites-into-tensions/2020/01/05/417241ba-2fc6-11ea-971b-43bec3ff9860_story.html |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Trump subsequently insisted he would not hesitate to destroy such targets even after some said it could be considered a war crime.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/05/us/politics/trump-iran-cultural-sites.html?campaign_id=60&instance_id=0&segment_id=20074&user_id=e9848bda5d7546386411f6e2fbdaf95e&regi_id=16153474 |title=Trump Reiterates Threat to Target Iranian Cultural Sites |last=Haberman |first=Maggie |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmerican politicians reacted along party lines. [[Majority leader of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] celebrated the attack, referring to Soleimani as \"Iran's master terrorist\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/mcconnell-lauds-iranian-generals-killing-schumer-decries-lack/story?id=68052592 |title=McConnell lauds Iranian general's killing as Schumer decries lack of consultation with Congress |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=6 January 2020 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105232855/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/mcconnell-lauds-iranian-generals-killing-schumer-decries-lack/story?id=68052592 |archive-date=5 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] referred to the attacks as \"provocative and disproportionate\", and introduced a \"war powers resolution\" requiring Trump's administration to end hostilities with Iran not approved by Congress within 30 days.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/fa2f21ce-3042-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |title=Pelosi seeks to curb Trump's ability to strike Iran |last=Politi |first=James |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107010056/https://www.ft.com/content/fa2f21ce-3042-11ea-9703-eea0cae3f0de |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Senator [[Lindsey Graham]] tweeted \"To the Iranian government: if you want more, you will get more.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/politics/lindsey-graham-suleimani-drone-strike/index.html |title=Lindsey Graham says he was briefed ahead of strike, while Democratic leaders were not |last=Stracqualursi |first=Veronica |date=3 January 2020 |access-date=12 January 2020 |website=[[CNN]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112034356/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/03/politics/lindsey-graham-suleimani-drone-strike/index.html |archive-date=12 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> On the other hand, Senator [[Richard Blumenthal]] stated, \"The present authorizations for use of military force in no way cover starting a possible new war. This step could bring the most consequential military confrontation in decades.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The Democratic candidates for the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], political challengers to Trump, largely condemned the airstrike.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/02/soleimani-2020-iran-democrats-093123 |title=2020 Dems warn of escalation in Middle East after Soleimani killing |last=Choi |first=Matthew |date=3 January 2020 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103071024/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/02/soleimani-2020-iran-democrats-093123 |archive-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> One candidate described the killing as a [[wag the dog]] incident,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/jan/05/impeachment-warren-trump-wag-the-dog-qassem-suleimani-iran |title=Impeachment: Warren accuses Trump of 'wag the dog' strike on Suleimani |last=Pengelly |first=Martin |date=5 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |url-status=live |last2=Helmore |first2=Edward |access-date=5 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105173029/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/jan/05/impeachment-warren-trump-wag-the-dog-qassem-suleimani-iran |archive-date=5 January 2020 }}</ref> parallel to the bombing of Iraq, [[Afghanistan]], and [[Sudan]] by president [[Bill Clinton]] during his [[Impeachment of Bill Clinton|impeachment process]].<ref>[https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/clinton-airstrike-impeachment/ Clinton launched an airstrike on Iraq amid impeachment proceedings against him in 1998.] Snopes.</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of New York City|New York City Mayor]] [[Bill de Blasio]] put the [[New York City Police Department|police department]] on high alert, including the potential of bag checks at subway stations and vehicle checks at tunnels and bridges.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/03/de-blasio-hints-new-yorkers-may-face-subway-bag-checks-after-death-of-iran-general/ |title=De Blasio hints New Yorkers may face subway bag checks after death of Iran general |last=Calder |first=Rich |date=3 January 2020 |website=[[New York Post]] |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103204923/https://nypost.com/2020/01/03/de-blasio-hints-new-yorkers-may-face-subway-bag-checks-after-death-of-iran-general/ |archive-date=3 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:NATO Secretary General Press Point Following NAC Meeting DOD 107573162-5e1670a17bd38.webm|thumb|right|upright=0.9|[[NATO]] Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] remarks]]\n\n[[United Nations]] [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary-General]] [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]] expressed concern over the escalation and called for leaders to \"exercise maximum restraint\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/01/1054701 |title=UN chief calls for de-escalation across Gulf region after killing of top Iranian General in US airstrike |date=3 January 2020 |work=UN News |access-date=4 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104005230/https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/01/1054701 |archive-date=4 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[NATO]] [[Secretary General of NATO|Secretary General]] [[Jens Stoltenberg]] said, following a meeting on 6{{nbsp}}January, \"all members of the Atlantic alliance stood behind the United States in the Middle East\" and that \"Iran must refrain from further violence and provocations.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-nato/us-briefs-nato-over-iran-strike-avoids-european-criticism-idUSKBN1Z51SI |title=U.S. briefs NATO over Iran strike, avoids European criticism |last=Emmott |first=Robin |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106221617/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-nato/us-briefs-nato-over-iran-strike-avoids-european-criticism-idUSKBN1Z51SI |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January, [[Russia]] and [[China]] were blamed by the U.S. because of \"blocking a resolution condemning the attack on Washington's Baghdad embassy\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/c4edd3820a971b78394df101952383f1 |title=The Latest: Iraq seeks Security Council condemnation of US |date=6 January 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106220240/https://apnews.com/c4edd3820a971b78394df101952383f1 |archive-date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/americas/us-says-china-russia-halted-resolution-on-iraq-embassy/1694236 |title=US says China, Russia halted resolution on Iraq embassy |website=AA |access-date=6 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107135256/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/americas/us-says-china-russia-halted-resolution-on-iraq-embassy/1694236 |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defense]], \"Russia has offered Iraq their S-400 air defense system to protect their airspace\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/31753/russia-re-ups-offer-to-arm-iraq-with-s-400-air-defenses-as-relations-with-the-u-s-sour |title=Russia Re-ups Offer To Arm Iraq With S-400 Air Defenses As Relations with the U.S. Sour |website=the drive |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108051603/https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/31753/russia-re-ups-offer-to-arm-iraq-with-s-400-air-defenses-as-relations-with-the-u-s-sour |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/russia-offers-iraq-s-400-air-defense-system-to-protect-airspace/ |title=Russia offers Iraq S-400 air defense system to protect airspace |date=7 January 2020 |website=almasdarnews |access-date=7 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107152125/https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/russia-offers-iraq-s-400-air-defense-system-to-protect-airspace/ |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> For only the second time since the start of the country's civil war nearly nine years ago, the Russian president, [[Vladimir Putin]], arrived in Syria to meet with its president, [[Bashar al-Assad]], on 7{{nbsp}}January.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-07/putin-s-trip-to-syria-after-iran-strike-shows-russia-unfazed |title=Putin's Syria Trip Shows He's Unfazed by Iran Tension |last=Arkhipov |first=Ilya |last2=Quinn |first2=Aine |website=bloomberg |access-date=8 January 2020 |last3=Caroline Alexander |first3=Caroline |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200119055034/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-07/putin-s-trip-to-syria-after-iran-strike-shows-russia-unfazed |archive-date=19 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In another meeting, in Baghdad, on 6{{nbsp}}January, Zhang Tao, the Chinese Ambassador, said to Iraq's caretaker Prime Minister al-Mahdi that \"China is keen to increase security and military cooperation in Iraq.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/06/middleeast/iraq-us-iran-tensions-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Iranians mourn slain general |last=Berlinger |first=Joshua |access-date=6 January 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |last2=Mackintosh |first2=Eliza |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107003451/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/06/middleeast/iraq-us-iran-tensions-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=7 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Commons category}}\n* [[Countering America's Adversaries Through Sanctions Act]]\n* [[Disposition Matrix]]\n* [[Timeline of United States military operations]]\n* [[2020 in Iran]]\n* [[2020 in Iraq]]\n* [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]]\n\n== Notes ==\n\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"RFarda_Jan2020_iraqprotests\">{{Cite news |url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/overshadowed-by-u-s--iran-escalation-iraq-protesters-keep-movement-alive-/30363179.html |title=Overshadowed By U.S.-Iran Escalation, Iraq Protesters Keep Movement Alive |last=Ahmed |first=Nabil |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Radio Farda]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107013824/https://en.radiofarda.com/a/overshadowed-by-u-s--iran-escalation-iraq-protesters-keep-movement-alive-/30363179.html |archive-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AlMon_made_in_Iraq\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/01/iraq-national-economy-iran-protests.html |title=National campaign to support domestic goods on rise in Iraq |last=Zeed |first=Adnan Abu |date=7 January 2020 |work=[[Al-Monitor]] |access-date=9 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107214102/https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/01/iraq-national-economy-iran-protests.html |archive-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"lObs_2020Jan_noUS_noIran\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nouvelobs.com/societe/20200105.AFP1556/en-irak-les-manifestants-anti-pouvoir-disent-non-aux-occupants-americain-et-iranien.html